m\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 It is lunchtime on a wet day in London and a group of stakeholders has gathered to give feedback to Vodafone, the world's biggest mobile operator by revenue, on its UK corporate responsibility report.\par \par \uc2 Ten people are sitting round the table, including a telecommunications sector analyst, a local authority planning officer, a representative of a think-tank, a sustainable development campaigner, the editor of an environmental journal, and me.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Discussion ranges from the company's handling of controversial issues such as the siting of mobile phone masts and the protection of children from "adult" internet content on their phones, to whether the CR report is too long or too short.\par \par \uc2 The debate, facilitated by a consultant, is polite but lively, and Vodafone's representative quietly takes notes.\par \par \uc2 Seeking out the views of stakeholders has become accepted practice among larger companies, especially multinationals, that are concerned to understand external expectations of their business and to manage their impact on society and the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 An army of consultants, including big firms such as PwC, is competing to offer companies advice on stakeholder dialogue and "mapping" - identifying key groups and ranking them in order of their importance to the company.\par \par \uc2 Stakeholders, often equated narrowly with campaign groups, can comprise a broad range of interested parties from customers, employees, shareholders and suppliers to government and regulatory authorities.\par \par \uc2 Such is the activity in this area that a new "stakeholder engagement standard" has recently emerged. AccountAbility, the London-based non-profit institute that created the standard, says its aim is to address big variations in the quality and effectiveness of companies' efforts.\par \par \uc2 BT, the telecommunications group, has meanwhile launched a "better business game" for companies, business schools and charities in which players act as different stakeholders discussing everyday business dilemmas. "It is not always easy to 'do the right thing' when stakeholders may have very different views about how a business should act," says Adrian Hosford, BT's director of corporate responsibility.\par \par \uc2 So what does a company do when stakeholder demands collide, either with each other, or with the interests of the business? And is the considerable investment of corporate time and effort in dialogues with stakeholders worthwhile?\par \par \uc2 "You couldn't put together an effective, appropriate corporate responsibility programme without an effective stakeholder programme," replies Charlotte Grezo, Vodafone's director of corporate responsibility.\par \par \uc2 "You've really got to take the whole thing seriously and be prepared to listen to people and take on board their views."\par \par \uc2 Vodafone's roundtable in London was one of many such meetings that the company holds each year around the world. It also commissions in-depth opinion surveys and holds detailed discussions with specific interest groups, both formal and informal.\par \par \uc2 There can be big advantages for companies in understanding risks and avoiding damaging publicity, says Ms Grezo. "We're really at the stage where people who have concerns will give us a call and have a chat. You would hope that if you have built up enough trust and respect with people they would have a talk with you first."\par \par \uc2 Yes, there are bound to be disagreements, she says. "But generally speaking we've found that if you work things through and are open to new issues, you don't get to that situation (of conflict)."\par \par \uc2 Mike Barry, head of \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  at Marks and Spencer, says consultation has enabled the UK high street retailer to chart shifts in consumer attitudes to supply-chain ethics, an area on which it puts a lot of emphasis.\par \par \uc2 "There has been a hardening of attitudes," he says, referring to annual research conducted with about 500 M&S customers. "Two to three years ago it was just an enlightened minority but now the vast majority of customers have quite deep expectations of things like fair trade and animal welfare."\par \par \uc2 He says good relationships with stakeholders - M&S talks to about 160 different groups including campaigners, government bodies, regulators and think-tanks - provide a "reservoir of good will" if something goes wrong.\par \par \uc2 "It's vital to talk to stakeholders because to a large extent they are the ones defining the risk. They define the bad and the good practice."\par \par \uc2 They can also help when a brand comes under unwarranted attack from a little-known pressure group. Mr Barry has been able to consult established campaigners for useful guidance on the credibility of such assailants.\par \par \uc2 He says he has never felt that disagreements with important stakeholders have been so great that he has had to reject their views or ideas. "We've always been able to find a solution."\par \par \uc2 Some critics of \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  say pressure groups hold too much sway over companies. But M&S rejects the idea that it gives in to campaigners. Every company has to draw the line, says Mr Barry. "It comes down to priorities."\par \par \uc2 Many companies make the mistake of asking stakeholders' views and then ignoring them without explaining why, says Peter Knight, a director of Context, a consultancy that specialises in corporate responsibility strategy and communications. "There's enormous fatigue about this. Sometimes it's just sucking people's ideas out of them rather than 'engagement'," he says.\par \par \uc2 He questions the relevance of formal standards and frameworks for something that depends on relationship-building.\par \par \uc2 "The people who will do this best are those who want to have relationships with people outside the business. In the same way, a good salesman will be someone who knows how to smile and remember someone's name."\par \par \uc2 Mr Knight offers the following advice: ensure that dialogue with stakeholders takes place throughout the business and is not conducted only by the public affairs or CSR team; if interest groups have misunderstood your business or your actions, don't get cross but explain your position to them; and handle disagreements in the same way you would internal management debates.\par \par \uc2 "Listen, take a view, and go for it," he says. "You can't keep everyone happy all the time." \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 20051128S204.060\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row