l\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 As one of the UK's most venerable cultural institutions, the Royal Scottish National Orchestra has no shortage of affectionate followers. But the challenge facing two men recently appointed to the helm of the organisation is to turn some of that affection into financial support by introducing American-style philanthropy to arts funding.\par \par \uc2 Stephane Deneve, the 34-year-old French music director, joined the orchestra in September, just a few weeks after Simon Woods, who became chief executive of the Glasgow-based institution after eight years in the US, latterly as president and chief executive of the New Jersey Symphony Orchestra.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Mr Woods explains how the funding challenge facing the orchestra highlights Britain's half-way position between the predominantly private money that finances orchestras in the US and the public money that supports them in France, Italy and Germany: "The UK, like so many things, is in the middle. You can either say we've got the best of all possible worlds, or the worst."\par \par \uc2 Mr Deneve, who had previously conducted the Orchestre de Paris, Orchestre National de France and the Sydney and Melbourne Symphonies, also realised he was coming to a very different economic \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 "There is certainly more of an issue here about finance than there is in France, because in France the culture is so much supported - by the state, the cities, the regions - that basically they don't need any additional funding," he says.\par \par \uc2 "When I came here I realised we are not in America, where everything is private money, but we are sort of half way, and I do love that in the sense that it gives us more of an obligation to really think about what we do and the impact of it. It was very interesting for me to be not only 'the artist' in his tower just thinking about art, but be more aware of the marketing - of what works, what is challenging for an audience, what brings an audience."\par \par \uc2 The RSNO receives nearly 60 per cent of its annual funding from the state-funded Scottish Arts Council (GBP2.8m or $4.8m), with the rest equally divided between ticket sales (GBP1m) and fundraising (GBP960,000).\par \par \uc2 "There has been historically in the UK with orchestras a sort of precariousness about the funding", says Mr Woods, "which comes from the fact that there's never really been a systematic attempt at raising money from the private sector."\par \par \uc2 He says the only exception to this rule is business sponsorship, which has been pioneered by British orchestras since 1970. But he says this is becoming an increasingly hard market, not least because such spending normally comes out of \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  budgets, or money allocated for marketing or branding - funds that are often hit during business downturns.\par \par \uc2 "Another problem is that 20 years ago, bringing people to a concert by an orchestra was a great piece of client entertainment. Increasingly today, because of the general cultural shift towards popular culture, it is internally more and more of a tough sell for culture to be something companies want to use with their clients - so you see much more diversion of money towards sport."\par \par \uc2 However, Mr Woods is in no doubt that the greatest potential growth area, to fill the gap between public funding and the cost of running an orchestra, is individual giving.\par \par \uc2 "I see in the UK the very beginning - and it is only the beginning - of a culture of personal philanthropy that has proved enormously successful in the US for every non-profit organisation. I don't underestimate the difficulty of it: changing cultural attitudes so that the act of giving money to a cause that you love becomes second nature. At the moment people see going to an orchestra?.?.?.?as purely an entertainment transaction. I give GBP10, get a ticket, I go, I enjoy it and I leave: it is like going to the cinema.\par \par \uc2 "What we have to do over the next 10 years or so is build a much stronger sense of ownership among the public, so that giving becomes second nature, so that they say: 'I admire this organisation, I love the work it does for young people, I love going to its concerts and therefore it is the most logical thing for me to give them GBP100.' And maybe the year after it's GBP200, and maybe the year after that GBP500.\par \par \uc2 "I'd like to grow everything. We need to increase the capacity of the organisation, to be able to pay better salaries, attract and pay better guest conductors and soloists, we need to be able to spend more money to raise more money, and we need to spend more on marketing to sell more tickets."\par \par \uc2 The RSNO has established both a development board, charged with fundraising, and a council, which has an ambassadorial, door-opening function, to encourage private giving.\par \par \uc2 Mr Woods says: "It's a sort of upwards spiral what we're about, so we can do more of everything. The trouble is, many arts organisations find themselves in a downward spiral, and they can never break out of this fundamental capacity problem. The thing about private fundraising is that if you can get it right, it can help you break out of that circle."\par \par \uc2 ORCHESTRATING AN ONLINE REVOLUTION\par \par \uc2 A recent RSNO concert in Edinburgh was later made available to the audience for download over the internet - all for the price of the GBP5 ticket. Simon Woods, chief executive, says: "Classical music is tilted towards an older audience, and we were not sure what sort of response we'd get to it. But in fact a quarter of the audience downloaded some of the pieces."\par \par \uc2 In total there were nearly 7,000 downloads. "Other orchestras have started to work on similar things - such as podcasts - but I don't think anybody has done anything quite like this, which is to use downloading as a ticket-buying incentive," says Mr Woods. "We linked it to the experience, and said: 'Come to the concert and get to keep it.'"\par \par \uc2 Mr Woods says the question now is to what extent should their strategy be based around compact discs or downloads. "My personal hunch is that the adoption of downloading will go much quicker than anybody is thinking. Looking at my own habits, I just don't buy many CDs now - I download things to my iPod, and that's it, and I think there are many, many people like me. So I think for the time being we need a CD strategy, but in the long-term it's all about online." \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha