llowed to operate with impunity in developing countries because of the government's failure to enforce international guidelines on \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 , a report will today allege.\par \par \uc2 Gordon Brown and other ministers are accused of citing the guidelines as evidence of the government's commitment to responsible business practices but "lacking the political will to enforce them".\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 The failure to enforce the international rules, allied to the chancellor's "spectacular and irrational U-turn" in dropping the proposed operating and financial review reporting requirements for UK quoted companies, leaves the government's CSR agenda "looking more wanting than ever", according to Friends of the Earth.\par \par \uc2 The environmental lobby group, which co-wrote today's report with Amnesty International and Christian Aid, is this week expected to seek a judicial review of the government's decision to drop the OFR.\par \par \uc2 The report focuses on the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development's guidelines for multinational enterprises, governing companies' activities in areas such as employment relations, the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and bribery.\par \par \uc2 The guidelines are voluntary but the government has repeatedly supported them while holding the UK out to be, in the words of Patricia Hewitt, the former trade secretary, last year, a "world leader" in \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 The lobby groups that wrote the report will meet Department of Trade and Industry officials on Thursday to discuss its findings. The government is reviewing its implementation of the guidelines and the lobby groups hope the research will encourage ministers to take a tougher line on complaints about multinationals' behaviour.\par \par \uc2 Craig Bennett, senior campaigner at Friends of the Earth, said ministers and business groups had colluded in ensuring a "glacial pace" of enforcement. The guidelines were introduced in 1976 but it took until last summer for the CBI to commit publicly to working with the DTI in publicising them, according to the report. Only 12 of the FTSE 100 companies refer to the guidelines in their statements on CSR, a recent analysis found.\par \par \uc2 The official unit within the DTI, which deals with complaints about breaches of the guidelines, suffers from an "unwillingness to investigate and lack of fact-finding capacity", according to the report. "Despite numerous complaints . . . the government has yet to find a single UK company in violation of the guidelines," the report states. It cites as an example the failure to take action against any of the 18 British companies listed in a 2002 United Nations report accusing multinationals of profiteering from the exploitation of natural resources in the Democratic Republic of Congo.\par \par \uc2 The DTI said the government was "committed to promoting and implementing the OECD guidelines". \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\a