idctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Mining has an image problem. In developing and developed countries alike, the public tends to regard the industry as dirty, dangerous and disruptive - and those who stand to profit from it as greedy despoilers.\par \par \uc2 But as gold, copper and other metals hit their highest prices for many years, and the power generation industry is poised for a big shift from gas to coal, the imperative to challenge that caricature is becoming more urgent.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 While mine companies are making record profits, and mining stocks are attracting swaths of new investors, the risk of reputational damage is also rising as easy-to-reach deposits of metals, coal and diamonds in locations such as Australia and Canada are exhausted, forcing mining companies to expand into more remote areas of Africa, Asia and Latin America.\par \par \uc2 The critical voices are loud and well organised. But the industry is fighting back - admitting to past failings but trumpeting the message that, at a time when many fund managers use \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  as an important criterion for investment, it has cleaned up its act.\par \par \uc2 Fierce criticism of the environmental and social impact of mining is nothing new. The industry has long had a reputation for making large profits in poor countries and leaving nothing but environmental and social havoc in its wake.\par \par \uc2 Typical of the protest movement is Earthworks, a US-based non-governmental organisation that since 2004 has been running a campaign called No Dirty Gold. It accuses gold producers of using cyanide to recover greater amounts of metal and of wrecking traditional ways of life. Like many NGOs, it argues that poor but mineral-rich countries are held back by the "resource curse": profits from mining enrich foreign companies and a small, corrupt elite in government but not local communities.\par \par \uc2 Bobby Godsell, chief executive of AngloGold Ashanti of South Africa, one of the world's largest gold producers, argues that mining is no more inherently harmful than any other form of economic activity. But he admits that not all companies are responsible corporate citizens. "There is the possibility of 'good mining' - and you can find good projects all over the world. But there are also bad projects," he acknowledges.\par \par \uc2 In the 1960s, the mining industry pursued growth at all costs. The result was accidents and environmental damage. But in the 1970s the strategy began to be questioned. Mr Godsell says pressure from governments, NGOs and shareholders was pivotal although he argues that executives' consciences also played a part.\par \par \uc2 But far from abating, protest movements have grown, in part because the internet has opened avenues of complaint to once-disenfranchised communities. Recent examples of anti-mining protests include objections to the Rio Blanco copper project in Peru, owned by Monterrico Metals of London, and hostility encountered by Newmont, the US gold producer, in Indonesia. In 2001, several big mining companies decided that action was needed to tackle their industry's poor image. They formed the International Council on Mining and Metals, a grouping that styles itself as "the responsible face of mining".\par \par \uc2 This made good business sense, companies say. As graduates increasingly shun "old" industries, the mining sector is facing a shortage of new talent and companies hope a rehabilitation of the industry's reputation could help attract young blood.\par \par \uc2 In its first five years the ICMM has had plenty to keep it busy. While accidents are less frequent than they used to be, issues of waste disposal and the use of toxic chemicals remain. Newmont is currently locked in a battle with local people, NGOs and politicians in Indonesia over whether the gold company dumped toxic waste into Buyat Bay, near its now-closed Minahasa Raya mine, and consequently poisoned villagers. Newmont admits to dumping the waste but insists it had been treated and was harmless. Wayne Murdy, chief executive of Newmont, has since said the dispute was more to do with a breakdown in relations with the local community than the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  itself.\par \par \uc2 An example of ICMM's proactive approach concerns cyanide - which, though highly toxic, is widely used in the recovery of gold because it allows metal to be retrieved from low-grade ore. In an attempt to ease criticism of the chemical, the ICMM has developed the "Cyanide Code", a voluntary list of guidelines for the safe application of the poison in gold mining.\par \par \uc2 It is not simply reputations that are at stake. The World Bank, through its International Finance Corporation arm, controversially helps finance mining and oil and gas projects around the world. But access to the funding depends on companies' capacity to make a convincing case that their approach to the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and affected communities is "sustainable", in the jargon.\par \par \uc2 In 2004, the Extractive Industries Review, an independent report commissioned by the World Bank, recommended a halt to this funding, because of the industries' negative side-effects. The bank rejected this recommendation and pledged to fund more projects than ever. But it undertook to get involved with projects earlier, so its standards on the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and community engagement were met.\par \par \uc2 Rashad Kaldany, director of oil, gas, mining and chemicals at the World Bank/IFC, insists past problems have been resolved, maintaining: "The use of cyanide should not be an issue in a well-run mine today." But he says communities near to mines "have legitimate worries" based on past pollution incidents. Again, the problem often boils down to a lack of communication between mining companies and local people. If mining companies go against their natural instinct to keep a low profile, and try to engage local communities, protests can be avoided, says the World Bank.\par \par \uc2 There are some signs that companies' claims to have got to grips with the environmental side-effects of what they do in recent years are well-founded. They are making more efforts to study the ecosystem in an area before they start work and to limit the damage that mining does to plant and animal life. Generally, the industry is starting to compile better environmental data - on water quality, for example - before mines are built. The World Bank is encouraging this, in part so they can counter any subsequent accusations of pollution.\par \par \uc2 Perhaps the most striking example of a company that has sought to shed a reputation for environmental irresponsibility is Rio Tinto of the UK. It spent several years working on the preservation of biodiversity before proceeding with its controversial ilmenite project in Fort-Dauphin, Madagascar.\par \par \uc2 This represents a big cultural shift. As one of the first large diversified mining companies listed on the London Stock Exchange, Rio Tinto was for many years the bete-noire of environmental groups, who used regularly to picket its annual shareholder meetings. "It is ridiculous to say that mining is not intrusive for the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  - but we can minimise the intrusiveness," says Andrew Vickerman, Rio Tinto's head of communication and sustainable development. The company has got better at explaining itself, he says, and he talks to a full range of NGOs, from well-established organisations such as Oxfam and Greenpeace to more radical groups. "Our approach to engagement changed about a decade ago. There was a realisation that reputation is hugely important." There is a clear commercial pay-off, he acknowledges. "If we prove we can mine responsibly, it will get us access to new resources."\par \par \uc2 Mr Kaldany at the World Bank says that "many of the most important players in the industry take the issue of sustainable development very seriously" but smaller mining companies do not always adhere to the new standards. Mr Vickerman at Rio Tinto accepts that this is a problem for the sector. "The mining industry is judged by its worst performers and there are some real cowboys out there."\par \par \uc2 Now a new front is opening up for the industry: the need to tackle the social fall-out from its activities. That can range from the spread of HIV/Aids by migrant workers to increased government corruption and broader questions about whether indigenous populations are reaping an appropriate share of the spoils.\par \par \uc2 Critics point out that examples of communities made rich by mining are sparse. Botswana's economy has grown fast as a result of revenues from diamond mining but, even there, people are worried about what will happen to the economy after the mines are closed. The World Bank is encouraging the development of other types of economic activity in mining regions, so that people are not so dependent on finite mineral resources.\par \par \uc2 But investors may query whether a need to appease environmental and social campaigners is leading companies to assume a role that more properly belongs to governments.\par \par \uc2 In the poorest countries, mining companies often find themselves building infrastructure such as roads, schools and hospitals. Not surprisingly, these companies are sometimes attacked as proxies for the government. In such cases, the World Bank is pursuing a policy of "capacity building", a mixture of education, training and anti-corruption measures. Although it is not mining companies' responsibility to ensure governments function properly, it is in their interests, the bank argues.\par \par \uc2 Mr Kaldany says mining companies should focus on winning local support. For example, jobs should go to local, rather than imported workers. "If local communities do not feel they are benefiting from mining, I don't think the image of the industry will change."\par \par \uc2 There are signs that investors agree. Todd Warren, who manages mining and energy stocks for First State Investments, says he would avoid investing in a company that had put aside insufficient money to cover environmental issues, especially for the clean-up of the site after closure. "The mining industry can no longer operate without taking environmental issues into consideration. If they do, these issues will come back and hurt them."\par \par \uc2 Although an eye should be kept on corporate costs, Mr Warren says, the increasing amount devoted to the environmental and social side of mining is money well spent. It protects both against accidents and community protests.\par \par \uc2 "Bad publicity has a huge cost," he says.\par \par \uc2 RIO TINTO'S TORTUOUS PATH TO TREAD ON LEMUR ISLAND\par \par \uc2 By John Reed\par \par \uc2 On a strip of rainforest in southern Madagascar, women pluck and repot seedlings destined to revive ravaged surrounding woodland. The variety of seed shapes, sizes and colours attests to the diversity of local flora. About 85 per cent of Madagascar's plants are unique to the east African island; many exist on just one scrap of land.\par \par \uc2 "There are only nine trees like this left," says Manon Vinclette, holding up a palmful of knobbly seeds from the genus Eligmocarpus. While studying the forest near the port city of Fort-Dauphin, her team discovered about 10 plant species, a gecko and a snake that were unknown before.\par \par \uc2 The Canadian is the environmental manager for Rio Tinto's QIT Madagascar Minerals (QMM) project, which will soon begin mining ilmenite, used to whiten paint, plastics and paper. Ms Vinclette has been helping lay the groundwork for a decade and commands a staff of 60. She receives advice from a 10-member biodiversity committee that includes a representative of London's Kew Gardens and an expert in lemurs, the primates unique to Madagascar.\par \par \uc2 "Without the company, this forest probably wouldn't be here," she says of the 230 hectare (568 acre) forest. The claim is credible: local residents are felling other forests for charcoal or slash-and-burn agriculture.\par \par \uc2 Rio Tinto plans to invest $585m (GBP331m, ?483m) in the mining project, Madagascar's biggest inward investment. Due to yield the business-friendly government about $20m a year in royalties, it will also bequeath a port capable of handling other exports and cruise ships.\par \par \uc2 But because of the risks to the island's biodiversity, QMM's history has been tortuous and Rio Tinto has been under severe criticism from environmental campaigning groups. The company hired Ms Vinclette from Conservation International and Lisa Dean, a former country director for the charity Care, to examine the project's social impact. It has studied everything from butterflies to local demand for charcoal and the potential spread of HIV brought by workers who will build the port, and helped start an organisation for Fort-Dauphin's sex workers.\par \par \uc2 The project illustrates the lengths to which mining companies need to go to minimise the impact of their fundamentally "dirty" business. Rio Tinto has in the past faced warranted criticism for despoiling regions where it mined. But QMM's relationship with non-governmental organisations has gone from antagonistic to largely co-operative. Taking on board criticism from the NGOs and local communities, the company moved the location of the port and pledged not to mine on the endangered piece of forest where Ms Vinclette's team runs the nursery, equivalent to about 10 per cent of the mining deposit.\par \par \uc2 "The main turning point in our environmental partnership with NGOs came when we said, 'We'll set aside 10 per cent of this valuable mineral - and reduce our return - to protect the forest'," says Guy Larin, QMM's director-general. The project sets a precedent, he adds, "we hope not just in economics but in environmental and social responsibility".\par \par \uc2 Friends of the Earth, the pressure group, still claims it will damage biodiversity and bring local people little benefit. But WWF, the environmental charity, after a critical view in 2001 now supports the project, with qualifications. "On balance, it's very favourable to the region and favourable to Madagascar in general," says Martin Nicoll, senior conservation adviser for WWF in Madagascar. He retains concerns about dust, chemical and noise pollution but says the project will "create huge opportunities for direct employment and associated services".\par \par \uc2 Assessments and consultations resulted in the signing of a dina, a traditional social contract binding the company and local communities to meet certain obligations. Building the port is due to start this year andQMM will employ up to 1,000 foreign workers at a time as the project reaches its peak over the next three years. They will be confined largely to a purpose-built village and held to a code of conduct. "We can't stop all fraternisation but we can put all the firewalls in place," says Ms Dean.\par \par \uc2 The company has linked with donors on HIV programmes. Ms Dean admits that some preparations may be insufficient - or beyond the call of duty. "There's really no benchmark as to what's enough."\par \par \uc2 ACCIDENTS WILL HAPPEN\par \par \uc2 * 2006: A shaft collapse this month at the Sago coal mine in West Virginia, owned by International Coal Group, killed 12. The mine had previous alleged safety breaches.\par \par \uc2 * 2000: A truck transporting mercury from Newmont's Yanacocha gold mine spilled its cargo over a road in Peru. People who scooped up the poisonous liquid later had problems from blindness to memory loss.\par \par \uc2 * 1998: A break in the wall of a waste dam at the Los Frailes zinc/copper/lead/silver mine in Spain sent contaminated water into the Rio Agrio and the Guadiamar river near Seville. The clean-up took seven months and cost more than $100m.\par \par \uc2 * Early 1990s: At the Summitville gold mine in Colorado a cyanide leaching facility started leaking soon after operations started. The US Environmental Protection Agency had to foot the clean-up bill after Galactic Resources of Canada, the mine's owner, went bankrupt. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 46621884\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \t