pnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Surveys IPY1\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b PG\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 Page 2\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LA\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 English\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 (c) 2006 The Financial Times Limited. All rights reserved \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Pick a big company and you will almost certainly find an educational project to its name.\par \par \uc2 Woolworths, the household retailer, encourages primary school pupils to suggest how they would improve their playground. GlaxoSmithKline, the drugs company, tours schools with its Bio-Bubble, an assembly-hall sized inflatable model of a human cell that fits up to 40 students at a time; while Starbucks, the coffee shop chain, has collected books from customers for local primary schools.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 These projects are as prevalent in Mumbai as they are in Manchester and Minneapolis; a growing trend that matches schools' need for resources with businesses' need to be seen to be doing good.\par \par \uc2 Business in the Community (BITC), a UK organisation that advises companies on where they can make the most impact, says that of its 800 member companies, 90 per cent say education is the top priority when they are looking at possible social engagement.\par \par \uc2 "The past five years has seen an enormous quickening and growth in the expectations of what business will do and how it will do it," says Julia Cleverdon, chief executive of Business in the Community. "Companies are now pretty clear that they want to make an impact in schools, employees want them to, and governments want them to, as well."\par \par \uc2 Many of these projects are expressly intended to help profits and do good. A group of IT companies, Cisco Systems, Dell, Hewlett-Packard, Siemens and Intel, are involved in a project providing funding, equipment and expertise to schools in places such as Jordan, India and the Palestinian Territories.\par \par \uc2 Yet, as Alex Wong, director for information at the World Economic Forum's global education initiative, which has established the project, says, "it is not just philanthropic, but strategic".\par \par \uc2 He describes the project as a public/private sector partnership that matches the donors' skills and investment with the host government's vision of what it would like to see achieved. The project provides a low-risk means for companies to get to know the business and political \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , while building a positive reputation for doing good.\par \par \uc2 "We say to companies, 'if your project is philanthropic and you want to write about it publicly, that's fine. If your company is doing it because this may be a key market in five years' time and you want to get to know local business leaders and think of key future partnerships, that's also fine."\par \par \uc2 Such hand in glove relationships between governments and business are becoming a feature of the education system worldwide.\par \par \uc2 In the UK, the government has established 27 academies, controversial semi-independent schools in deprived areas, that are sponsored and controlled by business. These can decide what specialism the school has and, within the limits of the national curriculum, what subjects are taught.\par \par \uc2 In the US, which has a long history of private involvement in public education, corporate branding can be seen on sports stadiums, entrance halls and on the publicity for school events.\par \par \uc2 One of the reasons why businesses are willing to get involved is that they are having difficulty recruiting enough people with the skills they need.\par \par \uc2 Mike Kelly, head of \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  at KPMG, the consulting and accountancy firm, says it provides mentors to headteachers and numeracy and literacy support to local schools because it is keen to invest in the workforce of the future. "There are business and moral reasons as to why companies get involved in such projects. But the lifeblood of KPMG is a well-motivated, educated workforce so it makes sense to invest in that field."\par \par \uc2 But not all projects have such long-term interests in mind. Schools also score highly in cause-related marketing, where companies tie their support for an educational project with the promotion of their brand.\par \par \uc2 In a BITC index of money spent on cause-related marketing, schools came in second after health and ahead of young people in general, which come in third. BITC says Pounds 8.5m was raised for educational charities and causes through marketing programmes in the UK in 2004.\par \par \uc2 These efforts can be controversial. The UK's National Consumer Council, for example, is concerned about companies using schools as a captive market for their products. After a survey found that more children recognise a Nike logo or the McDonald's golden arches than they do Jesus Christ on a cross, it accused companies of operating with "the ethics of the playground bully".\par \par \uc2 This has forced companies to be more careful about how and where they get involved in school projects, and to withdraw quickly when they go wrong.\par \par \uc2 In 2004, for example, Cadbury-Schweppes, the drinks and chocolate group, was forced to withdraw a campaign that encouraged children to collect chocolate bar wrappers in exchange for schools sports equipment, after it provoked accusations of unwittingly fuelling a surge in childhood obesity.\par \par \uc2 Since then, McDonald's has decided to cut back its presence in primary schools and Coca-Cola has decided to remove branding from 4,000 vending machines in UK secondary schools.\par \par \uc2 But despite the rumbles of discontent, there seems to be little unified opposition to corporate involvement in the education system.\par \par \uc2 One reason may be that businesses are being increasingly sensitive as to how they portray their involvement in schools. Another is that even where there is opposition, the temptations of the new cricket pitch or library may just be too great. This suggests that schools and business are likely to continue working together in future. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 20060126S502.265\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 gedu : \uc2 Education | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | gcat : \uc2 Political/General News\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RE\b0\