s, trade unions and charities have joined forces to demand tighter rules on companies' social and environmental behaviour.\par \par \uc2 They are urging ministers to toughen directors' duties in a bill going through parliament, arguing that the government's plans are a "fudge".\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Stephen Byers, the former trade and industry secretary, is said to be sympathetic to calls in a Commons motion from 125 Labour MPs for directors "to identify, consider, act and report on any negative social and environmental impacts" from their companies' activities.\par \par \uc2 Over half the parliamentary Labour party not on the government payroll believe the company law reform bill, which has been introduced in the Lords, does not go far enough.\par \par \uc2 Mr Byers is due to host a meeting in Westminster tomorrow, organised by the trade justice movement and campaign groups including Amnesty International and Friends of the Earth, at which Labour backbenchers can be expected to discuss their strategy for tackling the bill in the Commons.\par \par \uc2 Peers yesterday began a line-by-line dissection of the legislation, the biggest shake-up of company law in 20 years. The legislation is intended to reduce red tape and contains other measures designed to make institutional shareholder voting more transparent and limit auditors' liabilities.\par \par \uc2 This week, the Conservatives signalled their intention to try to rewrite parts of the bill dealing with directors' duties, accusing ministers of imposing more onerous responsibilities on boardrooms.\par \par \uc2 Backed by the CBI employers' organisation, they said that far from slashing bureaucracy, the government risked impairing decision-making at the country's biggest companies. The bill seeks to codify directors' duties for the first time, saying they will have to act in the interests of shareholders but pay regard to the longer term and the interests of employees, the community and the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Business leaders, who at first welcomed the bill's deregulatory thrust, now want more flexibility built into it to protect directors from the risk of legal action. The Tories argue that the changes threaten to subvert directors' traditional responsibility to shareholders whose capital is at risk. It could even put off people from serving on boards.\par \par \uc2 The government is to resist these demands. Whitehall officials said the clause in the bill was a carefully crafted compromise that still puts shareholders first. It faces pressure from the parliamentary Labour party and trade unions to make directors' duties more explicit.\par \par \uc2 Sarah McCarthy-Fry, the Labour MP who tabled the Commons motion, is hoping to amend the bill, saying it was "cavalier" on social and environmental concerns.\par \par \uc2 "Many companies already report on these things," she said. "What I'm anxious to do is to bring on board what we call the laggards."\par \par \uc2 She added that the government could use its public sector buying power to encourage companies to take their \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  seriously, taking account of companies' track records when considering bids for contracts.\par \par \uc2 With large numbers of Labour MPs unhappy and the Tories also complaining, the bill looks set for a rocky ride through parliament. Hundreds of amendments are to be debated over coming weeks, ranging much wider than directors' duties.\par \par \uc2 The Conservatives are also concerned about parts of the bill covering "derivative claims", which set out a statutory process for shareholders to sue directors for negligence or breaches or duty. They believe this is heavy-handed.\par \par \uc2 Lord Hodgson, Conservative trade and industry spokesman, is angry, too, about a clause that will allow the government to change company law without coming back to parliament, something he believes is an affront to democracy.\par \par \uc2 The government concedes the power is "wide and novel" but has tried to reassure peers it will not be used for "large and politically controversial proposals".\par \par \uc2 Lord Sainsbury of Turville, trade and industry minister, says the clause is intended to cope with "a fast-changing world". Peers have urged its removal. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 20060131L102.100\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 c41 : \uc2 Management Issues | c13 : \uc2 Regulation/Government Policy | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | ncat : \uc2 Content Types | nfact : \uc2 Factiva Filters 