bl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 It has not rained for two weeks in Riau, in Indonesian central Sumatra, and already the air is pungent with the smoke of thousands of illegal fires being used for wholesale forest clearing.\par \par \uc2 "Yesterday . . . I called the police and said: 'I hope you take action straightaway. Otherwise, a month from now this whole area will be covered in haze again'," says Sukanto Tanoto in an interview at Riau, near the Indonesian tycoon's pulp mill. Run by his company, Asia Pacific Resources International (April), the mill is one of the two largest of its kind in the world.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Mr Sukanto, whose group was the subject of allegations of human rights violations and pollution problems in the 1990s, may seem an unlikely protector of the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 . But April is among a number of Indonesian conglomerates that are adopting western business practices in corporate and social responsibility in an attempt to rebuild images tarnished during the corrupt rule of former military strongman, Suharto.\par \par \uc2 This change is being driven by the rise of democracy in Indonesia, which has left companies more vulnerable to public protests, and the need to improve reputations in order to do business. Boycotts of products by some western non-governmental organisations are another influence.\par \par \uc2 One of Mr Sukanto's companies, Sateri, is expected to try soon to relaunch an international bond issue.\par \par \uc2 The challenge for these companies, however, is how to reform a corporate culture that was once unmoved by external pressure and to convince the outside world they are serious even as they draw up aggressive expansion plans.\par \par \uc2 Even by Indonesia'sstandards, the country's forestry business has a troubled history. After seizing power in 1965, Mr Suharto designated 75 per cent of the country as "state forest". He then awarded vast timber concessions to the military and friendly businessmen, laying the foundation for future social disputes with indigenous residents, according to a 2003 report by Human Rights Watch.\par \par \uc2 One of the most notorious cases was a conflict surrounding Mr Sukanto's original pulp and rayon mill, Inti Indorayon Utama, in north Sumatra, near the island's most spectacular natural landmark, Lake Toba. After it started operations in the 1980s, the mill became a focus for local opposition amid allegations of pollution and land disputes.\par \par \uc2 In a crackdown on protesters in March 1999, according to Human Rights Watch, police allegedly shot seven people, killing one instantly. Another 90 people were allegedly abducted and tortured or otherwise mistreated; one later died.\par \par \uc2 The company says it had nothing to do with the police action and that "certain parties" stirred up the trouble for "their own commercial reasons". But Mr Sukanto was forced to close the mill for five years and later diluted his interest.\par \par \uc2 The group switched focus to its flagship operation, the Riau Andalan pulp and paper mill, near Kerinci Pangkalan, in Riau. An imposing complex, it has sparked environmental rather than social concerns, although Human Rights Watch re-ports one protest, in October 1997, in which police fired on demonstrators near the mill.\par \par \uc2 Known by many around the mill simply as "the chairman", 56-year-old Mr Sukanto, who through his privately held Raja Garuda Mas International group also has interests in energy and palm oil, is philosophical about his past "mistakes".\par \par \uc2 "At that time [the Suharto era], we thought that poverty and society and taking care of the people was a government job - the government should provide me with security and law and order," he says. "So I think we learnt the hard way, we made some mistakes. In the end, we realised that when you come to a certain size of operation, you must have a very clear sense of social responsibility."\par \par \uc2 The crunch for the Kerinci mill came during the Asian financial crisis in 1998. Unemployed locals began raiding the site to steal materials; some were killed when they cut through live wires looking for copper.\par \par \uc2 "We saw chaos and we didn't know who to ask for protection," says AJ Devanesan, president of April.\par \par \uc2 Some managers wanted to leave the problem to the police. Instead, after an survey of villagers, they opted to launch a series of poverty-reduction programmes.\par \par \uc2 The company began what it calls the integrated farming system, under which it runs four training centres teaching villagers livestock rearing, fish farming and waste recycling to help wean them off illegal logging and slash-and-burn agriculture.\par \par \uc2 Other initiatives include "community fibre farm programmes", in which April partners small landowners to help them grow sustainable acacia plantations for the mill's use.\par \par \uc2 The company also confronted the problem of illegal logging by potential suppliers by introducing wood-tracking audits in 2002. Run by SGS Malaysia, an independent certification company, and monitored by the conservation group WWF Indonesia, these aimed to ensure its timber sources were legal. "The audit is getting better and better results," says Nazir Foead, species programme director at WWF Indonesia.\par \par \uc2 To help improve April's image abroad, Mr Devanesan says he began producing an independently verified sustainability report. Convincing staff of the benefit of such a programme took time "but once it gets going it becomes part of the culture".\par \par \uc2 Convincing outsiders will prove more difficult, however. Some forestry experts say the measure of April's intentions will be whether it can meet a key commitment to source all its timber from sustainable plantations by 2009.\par \par \uc2 Christian Cossalter, principal scientist at the Centre for International Forestry Research (Cifor), estimates April has planted only about half the 510,000 hectares of acacia plantations it needs to keep the 2m tonne-a-year Kerinci pulp mill running at capacity. He says planting is proceeding too slowly to meet the 2009 target. April says it is on track to meet its goal, and is planting an average 60,000ha a year.\par \par \uc2 Chris Barr, a scientist at Cifor, says April and its main competitor, Asia Pulp &Paper, built their giant mills in Riau before their plantations were ready. on line.\par \par \uc2 "I don't think anyone is going to criticise companies like APP and April for making investments in schools and development programmes," Mr Barr says. "But how do you weigh the benefits from those types of programmes with the very substantial negative impacts of clearing large areas of native forests?"\par \par \uc2 For its part, April insists it will not repeat past mistakes. Because, as Mr Sukanto says of the Indorayon case: "One thing I have learnt in life is that, once you get into that kind of trap, it's very difficult to get out."\par \par \uc2 The usefulness of scholarships and tigers\par \par \uc2 Raja Garuda Mas International is not the only Indonesian group turning to western-style \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  (CSR) and environmental programmes to improve its reputation, writes Shawn Donnan.\par \par \uc2 With some of the country's leading corporate citizens eager to reshape images tainted by links to the regime of Suharto, by the billions owed to creditors and by questionable practices long associated with Indonesia's business landscape, CSR is a growth industry in south-east Asia's largest economy.\par \par \uc2 HM Sampoerna, the clove cigarette giant that Philip Morris International bought last year for $5.2bn, has for years been known for a scholarship programme that sends Indonesian students overseas. So important is the foundation behind those scholarships to the Sampoerna family's image that Putera Sampoerna, the family patriarch, insisted on keeping control when he sold the company.\par \par \uc2 Asia Pulp &Paper is still best known in international financial circles for its 2001 default on $14bn in debt. But these days APP, controlled by the Widjaja family and its Sinar Mas Group, would prefer to be known as a saviour of the Sumatran tiger. Since 2003 APP has been working with Ogilvy, the global public relations company, to launch environmental programmes aimed at improving its reputation.\par \par \uc2 It has had missteps and forestry experts still raise their eyebrows when the subject of APP's environmental promises comes up. A memorandum of understanding APP signed with the conservation group WWF in 2003 ended in a split six months later that led WWF to lobby buyers worldwide to boycott APP. But APP insists efforts since then have brought genuine achievements.\par \par \uc2 APP last year signed an agreement with another group, the US-based Rainforest Alliance, to monitor its wood supply.\par \par \uc2 Aida Greenbury, APP's general manager of sustainability and stakeholder engagement, says it has also set aside 840,000 of the 2m hectares of Sumatra that form its primary wood supply.\par \par \uc2 That includes land where surveyors found evidence of Sumatran tigers.Ms Greenbury says the tigers have yet to be spotted but that has not stopped APP seizing an opportunity. In a "stakeholder update", APP boasted it was "taking a firm action . . . to protect the dwindling population of Sumatran tigers in Indonesia". \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 47297317\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CO\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 aspcre : \uc2 Asia Pacific Resources Ltd\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 i471 : \uc2 Paper Mills | i47101 : \uc2 Pulp Mills | ipap : \uc2 