djustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Asia Ed1\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b PG\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 Page 20\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LA\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 English\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 (c) 2006 The Financial Times Limited. All rights reserved \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 In the melting pot of Hong Kong, diversity is moving up the employment agenda. For the progressive company a diverse staff is far more than just a public relations exercise.\par \par \uc2 UBS, the international financial services group, is one of the companies placing a strong emphasis on the issue. The bank has dedicated staff in every region responsible for employee diversity and appointed its first global head in 2002.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 "For us, the business case is very compelling," says Kath Cates, regional operating officer for UBS in Asia-Pacific.\par \par \uc2 Shalini Mahtani, founder and chief executive of Community Business, a Hong Kong-based charity that works with companies on \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  issues, says: "I don't think companies in Asia are paying enough attention to diversity as a whole. Some of them have not realised that it is not just for good public relations.\par \par \uc2 "Research shows that the benefits of diversity for a company are innovation and a motivated staff, as well as a reputation as an employer of choice."\par \par \uc2 Unemployment in Hong Kong remained at 5.2 per cent in the first quarter of this year. But according to a recent report by Hudson, the international human resources consultant, the hiring expectations of companies in the territory is the highest in more than five years, with 58 per cent of employers expecting to increase their headcount this quarter.\par \par \uc2 "If companies want the best workforce, they need to realise everyone is different," says Ms Mahtani. "They can only get the best if they care about diversity."\par \par \uc2 Of all employers in Hong Kong, banks are the most optimistic for their hiring plans, according to the Hudson report.\par \par \uc2 Nearly two-thirds of them are looking to hire more staff to cope with the new business developments in China as the country deregulates its banking sector. This has translated into a heated competition for banking professionals.\par \par \uc2 "There is a war for talent," says Ms Cates of UBS. "We need the best people. To exclude any talents for any reason other than ability would make no sense."\par \par \uc2 Last November, Community Business organised a two-day conference on diversity and inclusion in Hong Kong, attracting 242 executives from around the world.\par \par \uc2 Lilian Fandriana, president for BP Asia, the oil group, was one of them. "To run a sustainable business, companies need to be able to hire the best talent available, based on each individual's ability to do the job, while also creating a work \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  that enables these talents to be fully developed," she says.\par \par \uc2 In Asia, the most pressing diversity issues are race and gender, according to a survey conducted during the conference. But the issues vary from country to country. In India, for example, the issue of race is associated with caste, in Hong Kong it is about being western-minded.\par \par \uc2 "As an issue, race in Hong Kong depends on whether you are overseas Chinese or were educated overseas," says Ms Mahtani. "There is a perception that if you were, then you must be more western. You will therefore have better prospects than other Chinese. If you have darker skin or if you are mainland Chinese, it is just harder. Some people think they are inferior."\par \par \uc2 According to Ms Mahtani, this perception is prominent in multinational companies with western managers, who find it easier to work with people from a more international background.\par \par \uc2 "It is to do with familiarity," she says. "Multinational companies talk about a global culture, but ultimately it is still a western culture. The way I look at it is: as long as there is favouritism, there is discrimination." But she agrees that it can be difficult to determine whether it is an issue of discrimination of the employer or competency of the candidate.\par \par \uc2 However, Terry Wang, who came to Hong Kong from Beijing three years ago to work at CLSA, an investment bank, believes discrimination in the workplace is slowly beginning to fade.\par \par \uc2 "I don't think I have been discriminated against at work. People in Hong Kong are very friendly. However, I agree that it is difficult for Asian people to rise to senior management roles. We are just not as aggressive as westerners," he says.\par \par \uc2 It is not only multinational companies that are dealing with diversity. Luen Thai, a Hong Kong-based clothing manufacturer whose clients include Liz Claiborne and Polo Ralph Lauren, says it has to focus on diversity because of the industry's fast changing nature.\par \par \uc2 "As the end of the apparel industry's quota forced a consolidation of suppliers to brands, there are only a few countries in which to produce products - namely China," says Frank Sauced, senior vice-president of corporate human resources.\par \par \uc2 "Consequently, customers from across the world converge in China, where they expect to do business in various languages and with people with different technical expertise and experiences."\par \par \uc2 Luen Thai now employs 23,000 people in more than six countries. Unusually for a Hong Kong company, 50 of of its senior managers are from south-east Asian countries. Consequently, it can also boast managerial support for its diversity ethos - something most companies see as the biggest barrier.\par \par \uc2 "Diversity in Luen Thai is ensured with the active involvement and support from our executives," says Mr Sauceda. "This support not only comes from policies and practices, but also from strong corporate values which make good business sense." \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 20060525J120.001\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 c42 : \uc2 Labor/Personnel Issues | cwkdiv : \uc2 Workplace Diversity | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | gjob : \uc2 Labor Issues | nanl : \uc2 Analysis | gcat : \uc2 Political/General News | gcom : \uc2 Society/Community/Work | ncat : \uc2 Content Types | nfact : \uc2 Factiva Filters | nfcpin : \uc2 FC&E Industry News Filter\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\