a society that reveres the sports star and the performer, admires the artist and the writer, but despises the wealth and opportunity creators. Indeed, business, industry and wealth creation are under attack as never before.\par \par \uc2 Business is not truly trusted and the sad fact is that to a great extent we only have ourselves to blame. This is not because we have actually committed evil, but because we have allowed others to characterise our actions and our motives, while we have been focused on doing business.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 The business scandals that still haunt us, from Enron and Arthur Andersen to Exxon Valdez and Bhopal, were the unacceptable face of capitalism, but they were in no way typical. Yet many people are more than happy to subscribe to the stereotype thatthe business world is populated by malignant people, determined to harm others and exploit the world forprofit.\par \par \uc2 Young people today are interested in the wider world and its future more than ever before and they are notseeing business as a place where they can feel at home. You only have to think of the recent film The Constant Gardener to see what Hollywood thinks of business. The Apprentice may be great entertainment but it is in no way typical of the reality in business. All this is clear evidence that business has a serious image problem.\par \par \uc2 We have to change this: we must declare that values have a central role in business and that if you are passionate about human rights or you care about the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  then business is a good place to be. We must start by defining and articulating the values of our businesses. Then we must live these values, auditing our performance against them and changing where necessary. Finally, we must loudly and proudly communicate our values and what we stand for.\par \par \uc2 Values are critical - they unite an organisation and provide the framework for sound and consistent decision-making. Right from the beginning, the Cadbury brothers wanted to be "a force for good in a troubled world" and "an asset to the neighbourhood", and they put their money where their mouths were.\par \par \uc2 However, the Cadburys were not just philanthropists. They were hard- headed and successful business people. They were capitalists with ideals and a wider purpose beyond the pursuitof profit. The Cadburys were pioneers in social provision for employees, in supporting the communities in which we live and work and, more than 100 years ago, were helping the cocoa farmers who make much of our businesspossible.\par \par \uc2 We still passionately believe that it is possible to pursue commercial goals and behave in line with values. What does this mean in practice? It means continuing to live by our values. Inthe case of Cadbury Schweppes, wecreated a main board \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  committee in 2001, oneof the few FTSE companies to do so, and put in place robust checks andbalances to keep us true to these values.\par \par \uc2 None of this, of course, was enough to put us beyond criticism. Recently, perceptions of us changed from heroto villain in the debate on obesityand consumer health. Almost overnight, a coalition of governmentcommittees, non-governmental organisations and the media placed the blame for an increasingly overweight society on Cadbury Schweppes and theentire food industry. At its extreme, the claim was that food, formerly viewed as a requirement for continued existence, was the new tobacco.This, of course, failed to addressthe not inconsequential issue thatwe have become a largely sedentary society.\par \par \uc2 This is not the place to rehearse the detail of these arguments, other than to record our strenuous disagreement. The simpler point is this: by being too quiet in the past, business has allowed the argument to pass by default, with very damaging perceptions forming along the way.\par \par \uc2 It is crucial that we communicate our positions and beliefs and why we are taking the actions that we are. Generally, the distrust has become so entrenched that rather than reach out, many companies have retreated and not communicated, fearing what people will say and what journalists will write.\par \par \uc2 This is a counsel of despair that cannot continue. We need to be our own messengers. We need to communicate what we think is important, what we stand for, what we are struggling with and what we are trying to do.\par \par \uc2 Remember Adam Smith's invisible hand? It is one of the most repeated phrases in the business world. But business has allowed society to forget a very simple fact: the hand that connects markets and balances supply and demand is ours. We are the people who put food on plates, books on shelves, music in people's ears and information online. We are the distributors and we are the creators of wealth.\par \par \uc2 We have allowed our argument togo unheard and we have, as a force in the world, sometimes preferred to be invisible. We can do so no longer. The invisible hand needs to become visible. If we do not speak up for business, who will?\par \par \uc2 The writer is chief executive of Cadbury Schweppes \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\c