360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Everyone knows good corporate governance must begin at the helm of an organisation, but for many multinationals it ends there, too. Fundamental principles - such as why one person calls the shots in a specific situation and another doesn't, or why one stakeholder group has a say in corporate issues and others don't - are left to trickle down inconsistently. Issues of transparency and accountability can also become more vague the further one gets from the organisational core. In this context, it is vital to remember that even the most powerful multinationals are dependent on their subsidiaries, the legally independent entities that enable them to disseminate value chains around the world. Most large multinationals control hundreds or thousands of subsidiaries via shareholdings. For example, in its 2005 statements, Siemens reported more than 900 fully-owned and 400 majority-owned subsidiaries or joint ventures.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Total, ABB and Daimler-Chrysler all report associations with about 1,000 entities each. General Electric, meanwhile, holds an ownership stake in 8,000 entities. In each of these cases, the subsidiaries are legally independent, with their own management teams and discrete businesses. Yet in aggregate they account for the largest proportion of their group's assets, turnover and value chains. As a result, their corporate governance is vital to the protection of not only their own shareholders (of whom the parent is likely to be the largest) but also those of their parent companies. Even so, the issue of subsidiary governance has received little attention to date. In 2003, the Global Corporate Governance Research Initiative at IMD launched a research project on subsidiary governance that focused mostly on European multinationals. The empirical backbone of this project was feedback from executives at multinational headquarters and subsidiaries. Overall, it provided insights into the main subsidiary governance challenges faced by today's multinationals, and how they should be tackled.\par \par \uc2 Three models for group governance Three distinct models of governance emerged from the IMD project, based on the ownership characteristics of the particular subsidiary involved. In the first, the subsidiary maintains a (supervisory) board that is active in subsidiary management. This model is often found in joint ventures and subsidiaries with multiple and minority shareholders. Examples are large overseas investments in China and India. The second model can be found in all sorts of entities: the subsidiary has a board, but its role is formal in nature - best described as a "rubberstamp board". Such boards are often mandated by law and deal with official issues only, for example legally required reporting. The third model, where the subsidiary is wholly owned by its parent and there is no dedicated board at all, is found in the largest number of cases. It is a "no frills" option that emerges by default to keep organisations as lean and efficient as possible. Under this model, group headquarters tries to avoid managing the subsidiary via a local board unless it is required to do so by law. The subsidiary management interacts directly with other management layers in the group, as if it were a department rather than a discrete company. There might still be some governance-related contact between the subsidiary and group headquarters, but it is only related to administrative, legal matters. For example, a group company secretary may need to gather information for the purpose of commercial registration.\par \par \uc2 The fallacies behind inadequate subsidiary governance In our research, no matter which of the models listed above was under scrutiny, the corporate governance in evidence at a group's headquarters seemed to be non-existent at its subsidiaries. The only boards that were active in the roll-out and maintenance of group corporate governance were those of subsidiaries that were not wholly owned - that is, those in the first and second models described above. Focusing on the third, predominant model, we argue that subsidiary governance has not emerged so far because of the following three fallacies.\par \par \uc2 - If your share price cannot drop, there is no need for corporate governance. The short- sighted group sees governance purely as a means to nurture shareholder value and the price of its shares and, therefore, focuses all its governance efforts on headquarters. It regards subsidiaries that are not publicly listed, and that have limited liability status, as entirely non-troublesome. In terms of subsidiary governance, their reasoning goes something like this: "You can't really price good governance into shares and nobody seems to benefit from it at the end of the day. No shareholder activists, pension funds or stock exchange authorities are going to knock on our door and ask us to improve our subsidiary governance." However, this attitude can leave group shareholders at a significant disadvantage. Subsidiaries are usually strategic long-term investments. Their shares are carried forward at book value. As a result, the group cannot simply divest and transfer its capital into a better-performing corporation. One Scandinavian pharmaceutical multinational we studied was faced with this dilemma. A product of high strategic importance got stuck in the development phase in an overseas R&D joint venture. Advancement through the local board was cumbersome, but the project was too important and the sunk costs would have been too high to simply call it a day and divest.\par \par \uc2 - What is not compulsory by law is not necessary for corporate governance either. When corporate governance first began to protect the interests of shareholders (in spirit if not in name), it was given the law to defend itself. But law has become a false friend, which has led to two fateful outcomes. First, shareholders rely on the idea that if something is not legally prohibited, it can't be fundamentally wrong. Well, honestly, it can. But it might take a couple of Enrons and WorldComs for the business world to realise that one-tier board structures (in which the CEO often holds the position of chairman as well) can create autocratic leaders. Second, now that the plethora of regulation and mandatory and voluntary codes requires whole teams of experts to "govern well", little time remains for efforts beyond the law. And for subsidiary governance? Regulation is scarce, and there are no stock exchanges or analysts scrutinising the management. As a result, what accounts for the legal backbone of modern corporate governance in most countries does not apply to subsidiaries. Consider the recent debacle at the Dutch supermarket giant Ahold, whose overseas subsidiaries misstated Dollars 500m in fake profits. Clearly, such reporting was illegal before Sarbanes-Oxley came into effect, in all major economies of the world. Corporate governance is different from legal governance but the latter can't possibly substitute the first.\par \par \uc2 - Subsidiary management takes care of subsidiary governance. Again, this is an inadequate attitude. Of the headquarters managers we asked in the course of our research, 93 per cent said managing subsidiaries means simply trusting the local management. But why should the principal suddenly trust the agent? At group headquarters, there has been a shift over the years towards a checks-and-balances model of governance - but not one that extends as far as subsidiaries. Hence, to assume that subsidiary governance is being taken care of either by local legislation or the subsidiary management, means relying on little to nothing. Or, in the words of one headquarters manager we interviewed: "The subsidiary board cannot represent the interests of headquarters because the CEO is its chairman." The importance of group alignment The core of the dilemma is clear: there is a governance issue but neither headquarters nor subsidiary executives really deal with it. If corporate governance protects the assets and returns of the shareholder capital invested, shouldn't there be good subsidiary governance, too? A group's subsidiaries account for a very large proportion of the capital invested by their headquarters in the name of shareholders. For example, in its 2005 financial statements, Berkshire Hathaway, the holding company of investment guru Warren Buffett, reported close to Dollars 200bn in capital invested in companies. In the same document, Mr Buffett asked: "Would our shareholders be better off if they directly owned shares in each of our 68 businesses?" As his company has outperformed the S&P 500 by an average of 11.2 per cent per year since its foundation in 1965, the answer is clear. The secret ingredient to this success may well be active subsidiary governance in the name of his shareholders. So, what is the main benefit of subsidiary governance? It is subsidiary compliance; that is, compliance of the subsidiary management with the interests of subsidiary shareholders. The decisive shareholder, of course, is the group's headquarters, so good overall governance depends on the relationship between the management of the subsidiary and that of the group as a whole. The issue of how to sustain effective corporate governance consistently across a multinational group is a new challenge that, in line with globalisation, is fast-becoming crucial to retain and build competitive advantage. It is no longer sufficient to regard group corporate governance as simply the way in which the board at headquarters operates and deals with the outside world. If subsidiary governance is handled badly, it can have a disproportionate impact on the group as a whole.\par \par \uc2 Choosing the right system of subsidiary governance for your organisation As each subsidiary differs in its capabilities, needs and local challenges, so too must its governance system. Our research shows that the larger a subsidiary becomes, the more important governance is for its inner life. During growth, decisions that were simple can suddenly become highly complex, so it is vital to have a system of clear responsibilities and competencies in place. A subsidiary's legal \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , including matters such as shareholder rights and managerial liability regulation, also has a huge impact on corporate governance. Moreover, an entrenched culture of good corporate governance - a "governance atmosphere" - in a country will have a significant bearing on the type of internal governance used by the local subsidiary of a foreign company. In the US, consumers are known for their litigious nature, and have a legal system designed to help them challenge corporations. In Germany, on the other hand, changes in corporate control are perceived to be unfriendly and unsocial. For example, some of the key people from Mannesmann who were involved in the takeover of their company by UK rival Vodafone in 2000 are still on trial defending their post- acquisition bonuses. If, like most companies, you have previously tried to disseminate governance principles along a chain of management teams, without consideration for the legal structure of the group as a whole, then you will probably find that a lot of the governance mechanisms intended for shareholder protection (for example, subsidiary boards) have been lost. However, this situation paves the way for new systems that are broader in scope and more versatile. For example, you could choose to send headquarters managers into subsidiary teams at any point to ensure governance issues are being handled correctly - something your group's shareholders could not do for themselves. Or you could implement a bonus system for subsidiary managers - a "subsidiary compliance bonus" - to promote adherence to group principles. One thing that turned out to be particularly useful for the pioneering multinationals we studied was to have a group-wide corporate culture form the backbone of subsidiary governance. It makes sense to have a corporate culture in which governance and performance goals are given equal prominence. Every member of every subsidiary needs to know what the group's guidelines on management, individual conduct and \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  mean for them, and what they can do to help the efforts of the group as a whole. So, why not invite the CEOs of your key subsidiaries to your next corporate governance workshop at headquarters, or the next meeting of your board's governance committee? Alternatively, you could begin dedicated subsidiary governance meetings, in which subsidiary managers could exchange past experiences. In the course of our research, we found that private equity funds achieve their governance expectations by enforcing comprehensive, written subsidiary standards in their investments. So, why not issue a "subsidiary governance manual" of your own?\par \par \uc2 For general success, be specific The best-looking governance approach on paper may not provide the best results if it does not suit the specific features of a subsidiary and its local \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Our research showed that, in environments that are complex, challenging and competitive, the best solution is to provide the management of the local subsidiary with more independence. This is especially true of markets where corporate governance principles are underpinned by heavy legislation. Here, subsidiaries will need to establish business principles and subsidiary codes of governance that meet local requirements while reflecting the principles of the group as a whole. It is crucial for group headquarters to find the right level of intervention into local governance matters. It may be difficult, for example, to keep headquarters in the loop in a timely way if reports have to go through a series of local or national holding and parent companies. Equally, it may be difficult to promote strong local awareness of managerial responsibility and ethical conduct if all governance efforts in the group are concentrated and managed centrally through headquarters. Delegation may be the best way to ensure subsidiaries translate group governance principles effectively, but it is vital that they are not given goals that they cannot reasonably achieve. A classic balance must be struck between standardisation, where possible, and local adaptation, where necessary. Traditionally, multinational approaches to subsidiary governance have been ad hoc rather than strategic. To find a comprehensive group-wide corporate governance strategy, you must ask the right questions. For example, does the introduction of group-wide governance instruments, such as an expert team at headquarters or an intranet-based governance information system, make sense? Group size does matter in this respect. We found that larger multinational organisations demanded group-wide solutions, and rendered others less efficient. For a small group, on the other hand, organisational re-engineering and direct subordination of subsidiaries under the headquarters might already do the job. Where resources already exist, exploit them; the contingent nature of the issue must not be a weakness. For example, if you are mandated to maintain a local supervisory board, why not use it right away? Joint venture boards could demonstrate the strategic contribution that active subsidiary boards can make. They could also relieve some of the burden from group headquarters. One global energy group we studied is currently reintroducing subsidiary boards - one for each country in which it operates. The board of the subsidiary with the largest business in that country is "reactivated" and given responsibility for all the other group entities in the country, in terms of local legal, regulatory and stakeholder issues.\par \par \uc2 Conclusion No regulation could probably have prevented the recent catastrophes at Enron, Ahold and Parmalat; and, by the same token, you will never fully know what is going on at your subsidiaries. However, it is important to strive for complete information and complete control as far as possible. If you are finding it difficult to get important information regularly from a subsidiary then you must take action, especially if it is impossible to exert direct influence or control on the subsidiary management and the local board is dominated by the CEO. Consider transferring specific governance risks to a local level; draft a code of corporate governance and conduct for the subsidiary; introduce business principles or even contracts with managerial liabilities and have all key people officially sign and commit to them. You should also ensure that all relevant stakeholders are aware of these measures and, when problems emerge, communicate transparently with them over your investigation and punishment of the wrongdoers. After all, to paraphrase Milton Friedman: "Subsidiary governance is corporate governance." \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clver