d you agree that banks are in a much better position to lead on the development of ambitious social, environmental and human rights policies?\par \par \uc2 We see already many examples of commercial bank policies that are clearly more ambitious than IFC's. - but a lot remains to be done. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.banktrack.orgIf"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 www.banktrack.orgIf}}}\uc2  so, why would banks bother with IFC performance standards as the benchmark for such policies anyway?\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Rachel Kyte: We think competition is good and we see a race to the top. This is good for banking and good for development. You and others will play your part in holding us all to account. I hope you will also chase any future freeriders.\par \par \uc2 From Arash Nazhad, Vancouver, Canada: How can banks move towards developing more transparent policies? What do you think it would take for commercial banks to increase their commitment towards sustainability and develop clear policies towards human rights?\par \par \uc2 Rachel Kyte: Disclosure to regulators, shareholders and stakeholders of what, when and in what form is something that banks are having to wrestle with in the sustainability debate.\par \par \uc2 Separating out reporting information so that others can see that the commitment to sustainability is more than greenwash, while at the same time not divulging confidential information, is complex.\par \par \uc2 The private sector's responsibility for human rights is now at the top of the human rights agenda and the sustainable development agenda. I think the challenge for financial institutions is to get our arms around the concept of complicity and make sense of direct and indirect responsibility for human rights.\par \par \uc2 Leo Johnson: The key to this has got to be reporting. The Equator Principles marks a key shift, from the generic "we will strive wherever possible to act according to reasonably acceptable practices, unless otherwise" approach to an approach where projects are governed by specific, and measurable standards. Disclosing those results will be a powerful driver of performance.\par \par \uc2 From Jon Sohn, senior associate, World Resources Institute: There is no shortage of sensitive issues surrounding the IFC/ExxonMobil-sponsored Chad-Cameroon pipeline. World Bank President Wolfowitz pulled the bank out because of revenue problems with Chad, yet the IFC remains involved. How do the new performance standards profess to change this outcome on future projects and what safeguards should the IFC put in place?\par \par \uc2 Also, can you flag five key issues that might be at the heart of a decision for IFC NOT to support an A) oil or gas pipeline and B) gold mining project under the new IFC framework?\par \par \uc2 Rachel Kyte: The decision to finance or not depends on a whole series of analyses of risks, country, business, currency, environmental and social etc. The governance capacity of the country, the laws and regulations that allow revenues to flow to development purposes are part of that assessment. The question of how the World Bank, and IFC, work together is something on all of our minds and something that Paul Wolfowitz, the president, is paying acute attention to.\par \par \uc2 Five issues that could be at the heart of a decision to not invest: potential destruction of a critical habitat; destruction of the traditional lands of indigenous peoples; lack of confidence that the project sponsor shared the same vision and goals for their business as us; lack of comfort that the project would lead to benefits in the country; failure by the project sponsor to engage with communities concerns.\par \par \uc2 From Aidan Ward: I would like to ask about the connection between sustainability as an environmental agenda and sustainability as an ethical agenda.\par \par \uc2 Leo Johnson\par \par \uc2 Rachel Kyte: Corporate governance is the third pillar of IFC's approach to \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 . For us ES and G (\b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , social and corporate governance) are vital. However, it is true that the G part of ES and G and its correlation to performance is better understood and measurements are more advanced. The weaker of the three is social. Yet all the evidence anecdotally is that this is where brand and business risk can be destroyed very quickly.\par \par \uc2 From Robert J. Piliero, CFA, graduate of Middlebury College: My (limited) understanding of "Sustainable Banking" is that borrowers would be denied access to credit if their proposed use of funds does not meet certain defined sustainable criteria. If correct, will this not place such banks at a competitive disadvantage to other banks? Indeed, will capital not simply flow to the lenders which do not impose such criteria?\par \par \uc2 Rachel Kyte: Financial institutions are talking about the standards of the industry and where they should be competing, and where they should be collaborating. Equator is a remarkable transfer of a public good into a private sphere. What started as brand protection became risk management and now is being used as a way to target growth and portfolio value for Equator Principles institutions.\par \par \uc2 Leo Johnson: One emerging issue is the fact that there is often an alignment of interest between the banks and their clients. They both face risks, whether reputational, legal or credit. The role that a number of banks are taking is to work with the clients to help them identify these operating risks, and provide value-added solutions that differentiate the bank.\par \par \uc2 From Ulrike Lohr: The IFC approved the updated environmental and social standards. There has been criticism by NGOs but also by voices from the banking sector that these new standards don't meet the higher standards set by the Equator Principles, a framework developed by the private banking sector. How do you see these criticisms as a member of the IFC ?\par \par \uc2 Rachel Kyte: It is a huge shift in our emphasis to outcomes and will provide stronger standards.\par \par \uc2 On labour issues the new standards are guided by the International Labour Organisation core labour conventions and for child labor issues by the UN Convention on the Rights of the Child.\par \par \uc2 On the use of experts to conduct environmental assessment: it is in the interests of a lender, IFC, Equator or anyone, that the business understand all the risks inherent in their projects or business models.\par \par \uc2 From Hamish Dingwall, Edinburgh, Scotland: Do you think that local economic development, enterprise development, alternative livelihood, economic diversification and supplier development initiatives will gain weight in determining investment decisions?\par \par \uc2 With respect to investment in the extractive industries (and all the problems this brings to local communities) do you believe that the above could become the "third leg of the stool" to compliment social/investment mandatory requirements..so addressing sustainability with respect to people's income generating potential? Perhaps only then, can we get "real" traction regarding these issues....\par \par \uc2 Rachel Kyte: The difference is between assessment and then development outcomes. You are describing the assessment and consultants process. Our focus now is on how the decisions that flow from these assessments are integrated into the operation of the company on a daily basis and then how they are monitored and reported to us as a lender, or to regulators and communities, where affected.\par \par \uc2 Leo Johnson: Hamish, you are right on the money. Bolivia, Nigeria, Chad, Cameroon - getting the local operating license is critical to making these projects and strategic sectors viable.\par \par \uc2 One of the key challenge facing the extractive industries right now is to figure out ways to deliver the economic benefits to achieve that operating licence. Linkages programmes - where the company supports local micro-enterprise development in a way that delivers economic growth, but also benefits the companies operations - is a critical driver in making that happen. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 49470189\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 ccsr : \uc2 Corporate Social Responsibility | genv : \uc2 Environmental News | ghum : \uc2 Human Rights/Civil Liberties | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | gcat : \uc2 Political/General News | gcom : \uc2 Society/Community/Work | ncat : \uc2 Content Types | nfact : \uc2 Factiva Filt