0\lin0 \uc2 In Romania, people seeking business loans from the Banca Comerciala Romana, the country's biggest commercial bank, are likely to face close questioning on the environmental impact of any project for which they need finance. The bank has 600 credit officers specially trained in environmental issues, thanks to a partnership with the International Finance Corporation.\par \par \uc2 In Hungary, Raiffeisen Bank has provided more than Dollars 7.5m in the past two years to improve buildings' energy efficiency, thanks to a similar partnership.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Throughout eastern Europe, commercial banks are becoming more conscious of environmental concerns - in particular energy efficiency, which is notoriously poor in the ex-communist bloc. They are doing so in partnership with the IFC, and also under the influence of the European Bank for Reconstruction and Development, which has made energy efficiency a key consideration in providing financial help to businesses.\par \par \uc2 In China, too, energy efficiency and environmental issues are rising up the banking agenda. The Industrial Bank of China, working with Xinao Gas, has begun to establish a loan portfolio of Dollars 58m to help small and medium-sized companies gain access to energy-efficient equipment.\par \par \uc2 More and more, banks want to be seen to be acting in a way that is environmentally sound - acting "sustainably" in the jargon. Lars Thunell, executive vice-president of the IFC, says: "We are seeing much more activity from all sorts of banks, much more commitment."\par \par \uc2 Sustainability is a watchword of the environmental movement. The most widely accepted definition comes from the 1987 Brundtland report into global environmental problems: "Sustainable development is development that meets the needs of the present without compromising the ability of future generations to meet their own needs."\par \par \uc2 Broadly speaking, this means protecting environmental goods - such as water, air, soil and the diversity of plant and animal life - from over-exploitation that is damaging in the medium or long term.\par \par \uc2 It means guarding against pollution and against practices that may compromise safety. It means limiting the impact of business projects on the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and cleaning up afterwards. It means controlling emissions of greenhouse gases, which lead to climate change. It also means an awareness of the social impact of projects, for example on the culture of indigenous peoples, or on the health and safety of workers.\par \par \uc2 All of these have been important concerns for environmental groups and governments. But, traditionally, banks have operated a fairly hands-off approach.\par \par \uc2 That is changing rapidly. It is not only development banks and their partners that have started to show a keen interest in sustainability issues. Banks with such impeccably capitalist credentials as Goldman Sachs, Citigroup, Bank of America, ABN Amro and HSBC are all lining up to prove that their operations can measure up on sustainability goals.\par \par \uc2 The changes are led from the very top of these organisations. Hank Paulson, recently nominated US Treasury Secretary, raised a few eyebrows when he was chairman of Goldman Sachs, with policies such as support for mandatory emissions trading. His nomination to the cabinet of President George W. Bush has given environmental groups hope that he will push a sustainability agenda at the highest levels of US government.\par \par \uc2 Jon Sohn, senior associate at the World Resources Institute, an environmental think tank, says: "He can bring a breath of fresh air to the administration on these issues. He has a lot of clout."\par \par \uc2 Sir John Bond, the recently retired chairman of HSBC, has also made clear that he rates sustainability as an important goal.\par \par \uc2 Stanley Fink, chief executive of the Man Group, one of the world's biggest hedge funds, spoke out strongly on his commitment to environmental issues this month when reporting the company's financial results.\par \par \uc2 For banks, sustainable business practices mean checking on the environmental credentials of businesses they finance. One of the key ways they can do so is to adopt the Equator Principles, which provide a set of clear standards on project finance. Banks can also reap benefits from ensuring that their own businesses are run on a sustainable basis.\par \par \uc2 The increasing interest in environmental and social concerns from financial institutions comes amid mounting evidence that seeking sustainability makes sound commercial sense. A survey of bankers carried out by the IFC found that 65 per cent reported tangible benefits from sustainable policies, including developing business in new areas and obtaining first-mover advantage in areas such as energy efficiency.\par \par \uc2 Once, the attractions of sustainability were seen primarily in terms of reputational risk - that is, avoiding the attentions of pressure groups that might campaign against a company for some perceived environmental or social malpractice. But today, says Mr Sohn, banks are driven to sustainability by hard commercial reality.\par \par \uc2 Rachel Crossley, director of investor responsibility at Insight Investment, says: "\b \highlight22\uc2 Corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  has been peripheral to (banks') core business, but they are now seeing that there is more to (sustainability) than that."\par \par \uc2 Several factors have combined to force this on to banks' agenda. First, high energy prices and concerns over energy security have provided an important spur. As the oil price rises, energy efficiency and alternative forms of energy that produce less carbon dioxide become more attractive.\par \par \uc2 Under Mr Paulson, Goldman Sachs instituted an investment pot of up to Dollars 1bn for renewable energy and energy efficiency projects.\par \par \uc2 Second, governments are also putting more constraints on businesses and individuals in environmental terms. Greenhouse gas emissions from rich countries,\par \par \uc2 apart from the US and Australia, are now regulated under the Kyoto protocol on climate change. The European Union and many US states now oblige companies to recycle many forms of waste, such as old computers. Construction companies must now follow strict rules in Europe on the energy efficiency of buildings they put up, while carmakers in China and the US face stricter regulation of fuel efficiency. These rules should make businesses that follow sustainable practices more attractive prospects for bank lending.\par \par \uc2 Investors have also been made more aware of the potential cost of environmental risks. Hurricane Katrina caused tens of billions of dollars of damage to companies. If recent studies are right, global warming could lead to an increase in the intensity and frequency of hurricanes. Can companies mitigate that risk by cutting greenhouse gas emissions?\par \par \uc2 Finally, there are also sizeable business opportunities in environmental sectors. General Electric said last month that revenues from products and services gathered under its Ecomagination brand, for environmental products, rose from Dollars 6.2bn to Dollars 10.1bn in the year since Jeff Immelt, chief executive, announced a new focus on environmental goods and services. These range from wind turbines to low-energy light bulbs and from more efficient aircraft engines to desalination plants. Mr Immelt told investors there were massive profits to be made in these sectors: "With oil prices and other energy costs surging and water scarcity concerns spreading, Ecomagination makes even more sense for our investors today than it did a year ago."\par \par \uc2 The area is still in its infancy, though. Emma Howard-Boyd, head of socially responsible investment at Jupiter, says: "There has been a lot of change in the last few years, but this is still early days. There is a lot more to come." \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 20060612S101.306\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CO\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 rombnk : \uc2 Banca Comerciala Romana SA\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IN\b0\cell \pard