\li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Negative headlines are nothing new for the big league in banking. Thirty years ago, Barclays faced an intense student campaign in the UK against its operations in apartheid South Africa. In the 1980s, employees at Westpac, the Australian bank, stopped wearing their uniforms into work for a while to avoid flak from the public over job cuts and branch closures.\par \par \uc2 In a more recent example of social pressures on banks, the cheek-by-jowl existence of wealthy financiers and low-paid office cleaners in London's Canary Wharf has attracted publicity for a trade union campaign to improve conditions for contract workers at the world's leading financial institutions.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 From consumer debt and job outsourcing, to the risks to human rights of financing controversial infrastructure projects in the developing world, banks face a bewildering array of social and ethical challenges to their reputation.\par \par \uc2 But it is only in the past few years that campaign groups, realising the pivotal role banks play in supporting other businesses, have begun to challenge the entire financial sector to improve consultation, disclosure and social and environmental management.\par \par \uc2 It is also only recently that socially responsible investors have turned their attention to the potential impact on banks' shareholder value of these challenges. One example is a paper for pension fund trustees on the financial services sector produced by the UK Social Investment Forum (UKSIF), a network of fund managers, researchers, financial advisers and others.\par \par \uc2 It says short-term risks include high levels of personal debt in the UK and the US, the costs and regulatory backlash resulting from the mis-selling of financial products, and the impact on employee and customer relations of outsourcing back-office functions from high-cost European countries to lower-cost locations.\par \par \uc2 Customer service has been a big concern in the UK, where a 2004 survey by the National Consumer Council placed banks and credit card companies even lower in the public's esteem than cold callers and doorstep sellers.\par \par \uc2 In the longer term, the sector could face even tighter rules, reducing efficiency and increasing costs, if it fails to comply or keep up with regulations on the movement of illicit funds and money laundering, according to the UKSIF paper, produced for a European Union conference on \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  and finance in December.\par \par \uc2 Employee equality is another potential area of risk, it says. "High-profile discrimination cases that sporadically hit investment banks indicate a wider issue of skills loss and under-development across the financial services industry," the report says. "Companies unable to diversify their staff, which would enable them to understand wider international cultures, risk missing out on opportunities to appeal to specific customer groupings, for example Islamic banking and remittances."\par \par \uc2 Social issues affecting banks vary from country to country. Australian banks have had to become more responsive to stakeholder concerns because of the reputational damage they suffered following deregulation in the 1980s, says Graham Paterson, head of corporate responsibility at Westpac.\par \par \uc2 Increased competition led to a reduction in loan standards and an increase in losses arising from the collapse of borrowers.\par \par \uc2 Westpac has worked to rebuild its reputation over the past decade with shareholders, customers and employees, says Mr Paterson. Social, economic, ethical and governance considerations are now part of its "principles for doing business".\par \par \uc2 How can global banks cover all the bases? For HSBC, the world's third largest bank, there is no single formula, says Jon Williams, head of group sustainable development.\par \par \uc2 "Every part of the bank has to have in place the ability to recognise and address the challenges," he says. "Standards and policies are established at group level, and are applied globally. To support this, a network of sustainability risk managers has been established, reporting locally to their business heads and functionally to group headquarters."\par \par \uc2 The bank has different ways of evaluating widely varying issues such as consumer debt in the developed world and human rights in the developing world. "For some issues, we would be guided by internal policies, such as our sector lending guidelines for projects that have a high social and environmental risk, and for others we would be guided by societal norms and values," says Mr Williams.\par \par \uc2 Some global banks, including HSBC, have moved into microfinance projects as a way of providing financial services to some of the world's poorest people.\par \par \uc2 Responding to social challenges like this is important for the bank's "licence to operate", says Mr Williams. "In the current operating \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , it is impossible for financial institutions to ignore their social responsibilities." \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clp