ntbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LA\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 English\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 (Copyright (c) 2006, Dow Jones & Company, Inc.)   \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 LONDON -- \uc2 ASDA Group PLC\uc2 , \uc2 Wal-Mart Stores Inc\uc2 .'s U.K. subsidiary, plans to use packaging made from natural materials, joining a host of U.K. retailers with waste-cutting initiatives to reduce costs and attract affluent customers -- though some question the effectiveness of such biodegradable packaging.\par \par \uc2 ASDA\uc2 , which is fighting to retain its fragile edge over \uc2 J Sainsbury PLC\uc2  as the U.K.'s second-largest retailer by sales after \uc2 Tesco\uc2 , is trying to attract consumers who are part of the so-called ethical U.K. consumer market that research firm Future Laboratory estimates is valued at GBP 25 billion, or $47 billion, a year.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 By replacing its environmentally harmful plastic trays, ready-meals boxes and wraps with biodegradable materials made mostly from starch, \uc2 ASDA\uc2  also eventually may keep regulators off its back. Faced with mounting landfills, the \uc2 European Union\uc2  and the \uc2 U.K. government\uc2  aim to recycle 23% of all plastics, and U.K. retailers would no doubt like to reach the U.K.'s 19% retail package recycling goal, before it becomes a requirement.\par \par \uc2 "No one wants to buy organic produce wrapped in PET," said Ian Bowles, \uc2 ASDA\uc2 's head of \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 , referring to the polyethylene plastic used for wrapping and containers. "We have to act quickly before we miss the boat."\par \par \uc2 Mr. Bowles said that if the biodegradable materials, which decompose rapidly under natural conditions, are successful, \uc2 Wal-Mart\uc2 , which is also testing biodegradable packaging, will incorporate them into U.S. stores. "We share our know-how with \uc2 Wal-Mart\uc2  and there is no reason why they shouldn't use biodegradable packaging if it works," he said.\par \par \uc2 However, some question whether biodegradable packages are environmentally sound. While recycling reduces the total amount of new packaging added to the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , for example, composting biodegradable material releases greenhouse gases. All three majors, \uc2 ASDA\uc2 , \uc2 Tesco\uc2  and \uc2 J Sainsbury\uc2 , have recycling-promotion projects, and \uc2 Tesco\uc2  uses recyclable trays for its organic foods.\par \par \uc2 Tesco\uc2  isn't keen on the biodegradable market. "When biodegradable materials go into landfill they will release greenhouse gasses such as carbon dioxide, whereas degradable materials can be recycled," a Tesco spokeswoman said.\par \par \uc2 U.K. retailers are relative latecomers to the recycle-versus-compost debate, as are those in France, where retailer \uc2 Carrefour SA\uc2 , Europe's largest grocer by sales, said it has no intention to switch to biodegradable plastics. In Germany, strict recycling laws, with deposits on recyclable bottles and bags, provide a revenue source to retailer \uc2 Karstadt Quelle AG\uc2 . Dutch retailer \uc2 Ahold NV\uc2 's Stop & Shop stores in the U.S. have created a compost plan for all their organic waste, but they don't yet feature biodegradable plastic wraps or bottles.\par \par \uc2 Biodegradable packaging is still untried on such a large scale. Retailers using plastics and noncompostable products say that biodegradable-packaging capacity is limited and the companies set to make the packaging have no experience in the mass manufacturing required to serve a client as large as \uc2 ASDA\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 "There simply is no company that could produce such a bulk of biodegradable materials to accommodate its large production of plastic bottles and cans," said Andrew Mills, a spokesman for \uc2 Rexam PLC\uc2 , the world's largest can maker by volume.\par \par \uc2 In the past, biodegradable products also meant higher costs. But industry experts now say that rising oil prices may soon level the cost of biodegradable and conventional packaging because crude oil is used in the manufacturing of PET -- 8% of crude oil is used to make plastics, according to the U.K. Department of \b \highlight22\uc2 Environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , Food and Rural Affairs.\par \par \uc2 ASDA\uc2 's Mr. Bowles acknowledges that fossil fuel-generated power is needed to produce biodegradable packaging. "But as long as we have sufficient volumes of production, biodegradable packaging will be commercially attractive," he added.\par \par \uc2 Still, just because \uc2 ASDA\uc2  produces biodegradables, doesn't mean that its customers will use them to reduce landfill waste. The Industry Council for Packaging and the \b \highlight22\uc2 Environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  warns that depending on consumers to compost the plastic means much of it could end up in landfills with other wastes. \uc2 ASDA\uc2  concedes that it is asking for a little help from consumers.\par \par \uc2 "The ideal situation would be for households to store biodegradable packaging in a warm and humid \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," said Mr. Bowles, which is unlikely to happen. "This way it would take about two months for such packaging to decompose."\par \par \uc2 ASDA\uc2  itself has pledged by 2010 to recycle and compost all material used by its 307 supermarkets to avoid sending waste to landfills. As a part of that plan, Mr. Bowles said, \uc2 ASDA\uc2  plans to pack all its fresh food and organic produce into biodegradable packaging starting in March. "We are planning to start off with organic produce and move to fresh produce, including meat," he said.\par \par \uc2 J Sainsbury\uc2 , which during the past two years has completely recycled its organic and higher-cost food-product containers, also has a biodegradable plan. Sainsbury announced earlier this month that it plans to have 80% of its products in compostable packaging by January 2008, and to eliminate plastic from its ready meals and organic food. \par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.djreprints.com/link/DJRFactiva.html?FACTIVA=weco20060919000050"}}