strategy.\par \par \uc2 Recruiters this year rated Ohio State students highest for their ability to work well in teams, personal ethics and integrity, and fit with the corporate culture. They gave the lowest scores for the amount of experiential learning in the curriculum and students' international knowledge and experience.\par \par \uc2 "We have been impressed with how strong the candidates have been from a technical and analytical standpoint," says Martin Murrer, a survey respondent and a managing director at Sagent Advisors, an investment-banking firm. When he gave some Ohio State students a fairly complex case study from an actual transaction he had worked on, he says, "I found to my surprise that they did a superior job of analyzing the situation."\par \par \uc2 But, he adds, "the weakness has been that they do not come into the interviews with the investment-banking lingo down as well as" students at other schools.\par \par \uc2 Other recruiters like "the Midwestern work ethic" of Ohio State's M.B.A. graduates. "I find the students to be very driven," says Christopher Rathsack, manager of strategy and analysis at Capital One Financial Corp. "They are very willing to take on a wide range of assignments to help build their internal experience to advance their career here."\par \par \uc2 He also finds the career-services office unusually willing to identify a slate of M.B.A. students who best meet his needs. At other schools, he says, "I feel like I'm on my own when it comes to finding the right candidates for our company."\par \par \uc2 OHIO STATE ON OHIO STATE\par \par \uc2 (Data provided by the Fisher College of Business at Ohio State University)\par \par \uc2 M.B.A. enrollment: 630\par \par \uc2 Full-time: 261\par \par \uc2 Part-time: 273\par \par \uc2 Executive: 96\par \par \uc2 Annual tuition: $18,318 (in-state)\par \par \uc2 $31,671 (out-of-state)\par \par \uc2 Annual room and board: $18,837\par \par \uc2 PROFILE OF FULL-TIME STUDENTS\par \par \uc2 GMAT score: 662 (mean)\par \par \uc2 660 (median)\par \par \uc2 Years of full-time work experience: 4.7 (mean)\par \par \uc2 4 (median)\par \par \uc2 Demographics\par \par \uc2 Male: 74%\par \par \uc2 Female: 26%\par \par \uc2 Minorities: 17%\par \par \uc2 U.S. citizens/residents: 66%\par \par \uc2 Foreign nationals: 34%\par \par \uc2 CLASS OF 2005 EMPLOYMENT DATA\par \par \uc2 Percentage of job-seeking full-time graduates who:\par \par \uc2 Received offers prior to or within three months of graduation: 95%\par \par \uc2 Accepted offers prior to or within three months of graduation: 95%\par \par \uc2 Average compensation of full-time graduates who accepted employment\par \par \uc2 Annual base salary: $80,081\par \par \uc2 Signing bonus: $11,491\par \par \uc2 Other guaranteed compensation: $16,348\par \par \uc2 Companies hiring the most 2005 full-time graduates:\par \par \uc2 Procter &Gamble: 6\par \par \uc2 A.T. Kearney: 3\par \par \uc2 Capital One: 3\par \par \uc2 Three of the most famous graduates of the M.B.A. program:\par \par \uc2 Clayton C. Daley, class of 1974, chief financial officer, Procter &Gamble\par \par \uc2 James O'Brien, class of 1978, chairman and CEO, Ashland\par \par \uc2 James E. Rohr, class of 1972, chairman and CEO, PNC Financial Services Group\par \par \uc2 THE RECRUITERS SPEAK\par \par \uc2 Ohio State's most impressive features:\par \par \uc2 "Students are down-to-earth and easier to manage"\par \par \uc2 "Well-rounded students with leadership potential"\par \par \uc2 "M.B.A.s willing to work in the Midwest"\par \par \uc2 Ohio State's major shortcomings:\par \par \uc2 "Small full-time M.B.A. class size can be limiting"\par \par \uc2 "Some students have inadequate work experience"\par \par \uc2 "Salary expectations are high"\par \par \uc2 3) Brigham Young University (Marriott)\par \par \uc2 Brigham Young University moved up three places to No. 3 in The Wall Street Journal/Harris Interactive Regional ranking, its best showing to date.\par \par \uc2 Closely tied to the Mormon Church, Brigham Young goes beyond numbers and aims to provide "spiritual growth and learning." Its mission is "to attract, develop and place men and women of faith, character and professional ability who will become outstanding leaders capable of dealing with change in a global \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 ."\par \par \uc2 Many of its students are members of the church and have done missionary work abroad, an appealing feature to companies seeking bilingual managers with international experience. Recruiters also say they find Brigham Young graduates unusually mature and hard working, noting that many already are married with children and some have started their own businesses.\par \par \uc2 In this year's survey, recruiters gave the Marriott School its top scores for students' teamwork skills, work ethic, and analytical and problem-solving abilities. It was rated lowest for students' previous work experience, experiential learning in the curriculum, the career-services office, and graduates' willingness to relocate.\par \par \uc2 Accounting is Brigham Young's strong suit academically with recruiters, who named it the fourth best among all of the schools in the survey. They also selected it as the seventh-best school for teaching about \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 When he interviewed M.B.A. students at Brigham Young during the 2004-05 school year, Gentry Myler, a manager in new-business development at Hewlett-Packard Co., was so pleased with the candidates that he had trouble recommending only two or three for employment. "I was extremely impressed with the maturity and confidence of the candidates I interviewed," he recalls. "We ended up hiring several Marriott School M.B.A.s, and I have had nothing but positive feedback from the businesses they landed in."\par \par \uc2 Brigham Young's major deficiency, recruiters say, is its lack of diversity, with women accounting for only 17% of its M.B.A. students, minorities 10% and foreign nationals 12%. The school hopes to boost those percentages through its "diversity initiative" for recruiting more underrepresented students and faculty and offering special scholarships to minorities.\par \par \uc2 BRIGHAM YOUNG ON BRIGHAM YOUNG\par \par \uc2 (Data provided by the Marriott School of Management at Brigham Young University)\par \par \uc2 M.B.A. enrollment: 366\par \par \uc2 Full-time: 241\par \par \uc2 Executive: 125\par \par \uc2 Annual tuition: $8,200 (members of the Mormon Church)\par \par \uc2 $16,400 (nonmembers)\par \par \uc2 Annual room and board: $4,500-$6,500\par \par \uc2 PROFILE OF FULL-TIME STUDENTS\par \par \uc2 GMAT score: 660 (mean)\par \par \uc2 660 (median)\par \par \uc2 Years of full-time work experience: 3.1 (mean)\par \par \uc2 2.6 (median)\par \par \uc2 Demographics\par \par \uc2 Male: 83%\par \par \uc2 Female: 17%\par \par \uc2 Minorities: 10%\par \par \uc2 U.S. citizens/residents: 88%\par \par \uc2 Foreign nationals: 12%\par \par \uc2 CLASS OF 2005 EMPLOYMENT DATA\par \par \uc2 Percentage of job-seeking full-time graduates who:\par \par \uc2 Received offers prior to or within three months of graduation: 91%\par \par \uc2 Accepted offers prior to or within three months of graduation: 91%\par \par \uc2 Average compensation of full-time graduates who accepted employment\par \par \uc2 Annual base salary: $75,451\par \par \uc2 Signing bonus: $9,430\par \par \uc2 Other guaranteed compensation: $9,483\par \par \uc2 Companies hiring the most 2005 full-time graduates:\par \par \uc2 Hewlett-Packard: 8\par \par \uc2 American Express: 6\par \par \uc2 Ford Motor, Honeywell: 5 each\par \par \uc2 Three of the most famous graduates of the M.B.A. program:\par \par \uc2 Kevin Rollins, class of 1984, president and CEO, Dell\par \par \uc2 D. Fraser Bullock, class of 1980, co-founder and managing director, Sorenson Capital\par \par \uc2 David W. Checketts, class of 1981, founder and chairman, Sports Capital Partners\par \par \uc2 THE RECRUITERS SPEAK\par \par \uc2 Brigham Young's most impressive features:\par \par \uc2 "Depth of character"\par \par \uc2 "Older, more mature students"\par \par \uc2 "International experience"\par \par \uc2 Brigham Young's major shortcomings:\par \par \uc2 "Lack of diversity -- minorities and women"\par \par \uc2 "Not a bastion of creativity"\par \par \uc2 "Less passionate and intense than students at other schools"\par \par \uc2 4) Purdue University (Krannert)\par \par \uc2 After two consecutive years at the top of the Regional ranking, Purdue's Krannert School finally lost the crown this year to Thunderbird.\par \par \uc2 Its fall to fourth place doesn't mean the school is suddenly turning out less qualified M.B.A. graduates. Recruiters still commend its students for their technical skills and solid work ethic, but they have complaints, too.\par \par \uc2 In this year's survey, recruiters gave Purdue its top scores for students' analytical and problem-solving skills and personal ethics and integrity. The school received its lowest ratings for commitment to \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 , students' international knowledge and their previous work experience.\par \par \uc2 Indeed, recruiters complain the most about the limited experience of many Krannert graduates and their unrealistic expectations for their first post-M.B.A. job. This year, full-time students averaged 4.3 years of prior work experience, down from 4.6 years in 2005; the median fell to 3.1 years from 3.8.\par \par \uc2 Established in 1958 as the School of Industrial Management, Purdue's M.B.A. program focuses on quantitative skills, operations management, technology and manufacturing. Based on input from students and recruiters, the school recently added three new areas of academic concentration for its M.B.A. students: global supply-chain management, analytical consulting, and technological innovation and entrepreneurship.\par \par \uc2 That expertise is clearly reflected in the Journal survey. Recruiters consistently rank Krannert among the top 10 schools in the academic disciplines of operations management (No. 3) and information technology (No. 7).\par \par \uc2 Those technical and operational skills certainly appeal to Marc Hochman, vice president, global operations, for A.T. Kearney Procurement Solutions, who has recruited at Krannert the past few years. Equally valuable to him is the school's teamwork orientation. "The structure of the program demands that students work effectively in teams," he says, "resulting in candidates who know both how to contribute to the group as an individual, as well as how to lead a team of people with disparate backgrounds, experiences and points of view."\par \par \uc2 PURDUE ON PURDUE\par \par \uc2 (Data provided by the Krannert School of Management at Purdue University)\par \par \uc2 M.B.A. enrollment: 462\par \par \uc2 Full-time: 237\par \par \uc2 Executive: 225\par \par \uc2 Annual tuition: $15,276 (in-state)\par \par \uc2 $30,010 (out-of-state)\par \par \uc2 Annual room and board: $7,500\par \par \uc2 PROFILE OF FULL-TIME STUDENTS\par \par \uc2 GMAT score: 657 (mean)\par \par \uc2 660 (median)\par \par \uc2 Years of full-time work experience: 4.3 (mean)\par \par \uc2 3.1 (median)\par \par \uc2 Demographics\par \par \uc2 Male: 80%\par \par \uc2 Female: 20%\par \par \uc2 Minorities: 24%\par \par \uc2 U.S. citizens/residents: 67%\par \par \uc2 Foreign nationals: 33%\par \par \uc2 CLASS OF 2005 EMPLOYMENT DATA\par \par \uc2 Percentage of job-seeking full-time graduates who:\par \par \uc2 Received offers prior to or within three months of graduation: 94%\par \par \uc2 Accepted offers prior to or within three months of graduation: 92%\par \par \uc2 Average compensation of full-time graduates who accepted employment\par \par \uc2 Annual base salary: $80,621\par \par \uc2 Signing bonus: $13,855\par \par \uc2 Other guaranteed compensation: $15,786\par \par \uc2 Companies hiring the most 2005 full-time graduates:\par \par \uc2 United Technologies: 8\par \par \uc2 Ford Motor: 6\par \par \uc2 Procter &Gamble: 4\par \par \uc2 Three of the most famous graduates of the M.B.A. program:\par \par \uc2 Joe Forehand, class of 1972, former chairman, Accenture\par \par \uc2 Marshall Larsen, class of 1977, chairman, president and CEO, Goodrich\par \par \uc2 Venu Srinivasan, class of 1977, chairman and managing director, TVS Motor Co.\par \par \uc2 THE RECRUITERS SPEAK\par \par \uc2 Purdue's most impressive features:\par \par \uc2 "The technical and business mix in students"\par \par \uc2 "Practical curriculum means students are ready to contribute immediately"\par \par \uc2 "Leadership, quantitative skills and work ethic"\par \par \uc2 Purdue's major shortcomings:\par \par \uc2 "Inadequate work experience"\par \par \uc2 "Diamonds in the rough -- some students could use more polish"\par \par \uc2 "Lacks diverse student population"\par \par \uc2 5) Michigan State University (Broad)\par \par \uc2 Michigan State's M.B.A. program fell to fifth place from second last year in the Regional ranking, with some recruiters complaining about students' limited work experience and leadership qualities.\par \par \uc2 Still, the school remains a favorite of many recruiters. Ariel Moore, for one, considers the Spartans some of the most appealing M.B.A. students she meets. "We know the best of their students not only compete with students anywhere on any level, but also stand well above the competition in their dedication to getting the job done well," says Ms. Moore, a manager of major environmental projects for DTE Energy Co.\par \par \uc2 In the survey, recruiters gave Michigan State top grades for students' personal ethics and integrity, teamwork abilities and work ethic. The lowest scores were for international knowledge, experiential learning in the curriculum and the likelihood of recruiting stars.\par \par \uc2 Recruiters