p Japan's first formal market for emissions trading.\par \par \uc2 If the plan comes to fruition, it could turn Japan into an important centre for international emissions trading within Asia-Pacific, should the market take off in the region in the future.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 The European Union has a thriving market in emissions trading - trading by companies of the right to pollute. For many countries, it is a key part of their attempt to meet their greenhouse gas emission reduction targets under the Kyoto protocol to combat global warming.\par \par \uc2 A trading system for emission rights could also help to erase Japan's reputation as the laggard in innovation among the world's largest financial markets.\par \par \uc2 The Japanese financial market has suffered a series of blows to its reputation over the past year because of trading problems at the Tokyo Stock Exchange, Asia's largest bourse.\par \par \uc2 Emissions trading is also "part of a bigger picture", Noriko Mimura , an official at the Kansai Economic Federation, a group of local businesses, told the Financial Times. "Our aim is how we can vitalise financial markets in Kansai" - a region centred on Osaka.\par \par \uc2 Trading in Japanese shares on the Tokyo Stock Exchange's First Section has risen more than five times in the past decade, to Y459,136bn (Dollars 3,900bn, Euros 3,085bn, Pounds 2,077bn) last year. By contrast, trading on the Osaka Securities Exchange has declined 8 per cent to only Y22,657bn.\par \par \uc2 Sceptics say much depends on whether the Japanese government decides to introduce a compulsory system for emissions trading, as exists in the EU. The Japanese government has set up a voluntary system and is reluctant to switch to a compulsory one.\par \par \uc2 Ms Mimura said that even if the Japanese government did not set up a compulsory system, companies might be interested in trading emission rights "as a method of CSR (\b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 )". This would imitate the example of some US companies, which trade in emissions at a market in Chicago, even though the country does not have a Kyoto target.\par \par \uc2 Thirty-six business sectors within Japan's Keidanren national business federation have agreed on voluntary schemes, including high polluters such as steel and paper.\par \par \uc2 It is not yet clear, either, how many other countries are going to make emissions targets in Asia-Pacific in the future, creating international demand for Asian trading. The only other country in the region to have ratified the Kyoto protocol is New Zealand. But China, for example, has also started taking much more interest in the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  recently, for fear that its poor environmental record may damage the country's long-term prospects.\par \par \uc2 Ms Mimura said that, in Kansai, "we have a very long and deep relationship with Asia. So we were also thinking (emission trading) may be a method to deepen our relationship with Asian companies too".\par \par \uc2 Some emission trading, not as comprehensive as in the EU, is already carried out in Asia through the Asia Carbon Exchange, headquartered in Singapore. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\cl