ng on their impact on society and the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  could soon lose momentum, with "non-financial reporting" in future playing only a "very limited" role in sustainable development.\par \par \uc2 An internal United Nations-commissioned study, obtained by the Financial Times, argues that moves by companies to report on their labour standards and environmental footprints will remain a "niche practice" limited to trans-national companies based in industrialised countries.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Few small and medium-sized enterprises, or companies in emerging markets, are set to join the "sustainability reporting" club, according to the study.\par \par \uc2 The findings may raise questions on the value of such reporting, depicted by \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  advocates as central to boosting the accountability of companies' social image.\par \par \uc2 The trend towards non-financial reporting for investors and customers has been particularly strong in Britain, where 70 of the top 100 companies produce such documents.\par \par \uc2 The study predicts that by 2020 only 11 per cent oftransnational companies - let alone other businesses - will provide social and environmental data.\par \par \uc2 The 101-page study focuses on the Global Reporting Initiative (GRI), an Amsterdam-based non-profit agency whose measurement indicators have become standard-setters used by around 1,000 transnational companies and other organisations.\par \par \uc2 The leaking of the report is awkward as next week hundreds of companies are to attend a GRI congress in Amsterdam where a new set of indicators are to be launched.\par \par \uc2 Their preparation, costing Euros 9m (Dollars 11.5, Pounds 6.1m), has been financed partly by companies including General Motors, BP, Microsoft and Alcan. Al Gore, former US vice-president, and Sir Mark Moody-Stuart, chairman of Anglo-American, are keynote speakers.\par \par \uc2 The study was commissioned by the UN \b \highlight22\uc2 Environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  Programme, a GRI supporter since 1998, and was written by the Global Public Policy Institute, a Berlin-based think-tank. Achim Steiner, UNEP executive director, will discuss its findings with GRI at the conference.\par \par \uc2 Mr Steiner told the Financial Times that the study - which has already stirred controversy within the UN and GRI - "poses legitimate questions", but he believed that non-financial reporting had a bright future.\par \par \uc2 "Growth in these activities will expand, although the ways in which the information is presented will evolve."\par \par \uc2 The study, based on interviews and surveys covering companies, non-governmental organisations and other experts, says sustainability reporting will remain important for a core group of companies, but an anticipated "exponential growth" in take-up by others is unlikely.\par \par \uc2 It argues that there will in future be less pressure on companies to act, since the interest of governments in legislating for this type of reporting is "tapering off".\par \par \uc2 Last year the British government withdrew proposals that would have made reporting on environmental impacts obligatory for listed companies. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpa