e opposing forces of business and environmentalism are gearing up for a last battle over the epic company law bill, more than eight years since they first locked horns over the legislation.\par \par \uc2 The passionate tenor of the debate reflects the bill's power to polarise. A particular flashpoint is the bill's contentious codification of directors' duties, requiring executives to "have regard to" factors such as the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and employees when making decisions.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Business has warned this provision could add regulatory costs, with directors forced to document thedecision-taking process to ward off potential lawsuits.\par \par \uc2 But green lobbyists and other \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  pressure groups argue the duty is so broadly worded it will have little effect in practice. They are calling for the government to go much further, forcing directors to act to mitigate environmental and other damage caused by corporate behaviour.\par \par \uc2 The green lobbyists are also pushing hard for an extension of the scope of the company law bill to cover private, as well as quoted, companies.\par \par \uc2 Tony Juniper, executive chairman of Friends of the Earth, said yesterday: "It's remarkable that companies like Virgin and Asda are excluded . . . it's a gaping chasm." He cited \b \highlight22\uc2 Environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  Agency research that he argued demonstrated "nine out of 10 of the top polluters would not be covered by this legislation".\par \par \uc2 The campaigners hope to persuade the government to agree last-minute amendments when the bill has its third Commons reading next month.\par \par \uc2 Deborah Doane, director of the Corporate Responsibility Coalition, said: "The government should move (to extend the bill to private companies) - it clearly sees the value of a level playing field. We're quietly optimistic."\par \par \uc2 Significant changes to the bill's provisions on directors' duties and reporting requirements appear highly un-likely, not least because of the potential damage to Gordon Brown's reputation. The chancellor caused a furore last year when he abolished what was a core element of the bill, axing the requirement for all companies to issue an annual operating and financial review, giving the directors' views on the prospects for the business. This makes the effective reintroduction of the OFR via the bill a politicalnon-starter.\par \par \uc2 But Margaret Hodge, the industry minister, signalled yesterday the government might be open to further changes to the corporate law regime, once the companies bill was safely on the statute book. She stressed she was alive to industry's concerns, saying there was a clear risk companies would relocate if ministers "over-egg the regulatory burden".\par \par \uc2 But Ms Hodge suggested that she believes businesses may be overestimating the potential impact of the bill. Once directors realised the statutory statement of their duties did not unleash lawsuits or create red tape, there could be scope for tougher rules on social and environmental responsibility, she said. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \