ha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Business will be offered a "tit for tat" deal under a Conservative government, with incentives such as cuts in red tape balanced by a demand for greater corporate responsibility, the party's head of policy has said.\par \par \uc2 Oliver Letwin warned business the Tories were now "really serious" in their commitment to environmental and family-friendly policies. Industry cannot assume its aversion to the potential extra costs of action in such areas will render it immune from statutory controls under a Conservative government, he suggested.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 In an interview with the Financial Times, Mr Letwin outlined the "deal we're putting to business". He pledged that a Tory government would "do something serious" about factors that damage UK competitiveness, such as excessive and intrusive regulation, lack of skills and poor infrastructure.\par \par \uc2 "But there's a tit for tat. We are not in your pocket. We're not here simply in order to do whatever it is some big businesses want, if that is not in the national interest," Mr Letwin said. "We need to attend, and you need to attend, to the issues of \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which are also critical to the national interest."\par \par \uc2 He highlighted family-friendly employment policies, including the right to request flexible working, and "the effect that business has on our \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the widest sense" as two particularly important areas where the Tories want business to act.\par \par \uc2 "If you want a government that's going to trust you to get on with the job and not regulate you so much, then you need to work with us to lift the image of business," he said. This image change in turn would require "lifting the reality of business by accepting your responsibility . . . We absolutely have to get to the point where people see business not as an enemy but as a friend".\par \par \uc2 Mr Letwin argued that this shift in corporate image and behaviour could be achieved through the "right balance" of persuasion and coercion, and without damaging economic competitiveness. It's a difficult trick to pull off and he admitted the Tories were under pressure to flesh out their aspirational goals.\par \par \uc2 The Conservatives will not produce a comprehensive set of detailed policies until the end of next year, with tax and spending proposals potentially delayed until later still. Critics argue that this timetable creates a vacuum, with the danger that public perceptions of Tory policy will not be set by the leadership. Voters could be confused by conflicting or off-the-wall recommendations from the independent policy reviews set up by Mr Letwin. Next month, for example, the Tories' tax review commission is expected to call for radical tax cuts, in seeming contradiction to the cautious "stability first" message promulgated by the leadership.\par \par \uc2 But Mr Letwin insisted he was "completely unworried" about the policy timetable. The party's "worst mistakes" over the past decade had come when shadow ministers "leapt into specifics" without first agreeing an overarching policy framework, he said.\par \par \uc2 Mr Letwin accepted that the policy review process was bound to leave some element of the party's core vote disappointed. But he argued that David Cameron did not need to engineer a symbolic confrontation with the right wing to get elected. Tony Blair had had to reject his party's "Clause 4" to convince voters Labour had changed, Mr Letwin said. "A lot of people are asking 'where is our clause 4 moment?' But they're making an error. It's simply not the case that this is a party that has to reverse 90 per cent of everything it's been saying for the last 10 years."\par \par \uc2 It remains to be seen whether this consensual approach can survive the transition from modernising the party's image to overhauling its policies that will occupy the next 18 months to two years. But Mr Letwin, like his shadow cabinet colleagues, seemed disinclined to worry. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 20060930L102.118\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 gpol : \uc2 Domestic Politics | c131 : \uc2 Regulatory Bodies | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | c13 : \uc2 Regulation/Government Policy | gcat : \uc2 Political/General News | gpir : \uc2 Politics/International Relations | ncat : \uc2 Content Types | nfact : \uc2 Factiva Filters | nfcpin : \uc2 FC&E Industry News Filter\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\ri