ntials and becoming "carbon neutral" with almost as much zeal as they have for profits.\par \par \uc2 James and Rupert Murdoch, Sir Richard Branson, Lee Scott of Wal-Mart, Terry Leahy of Tesco and Jeff Immelt of GE are among the converts. The surprising thing is the number of US companies that paint themselves green, despite the indifference of George W. Bush's administration to global warming and its opposition to the Kyoto treaty and the capping of carbon dioxide emissions.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 But consider this. If you were a chief executive trying to improve your company's image and reputation for \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which would you rather do? Increase your costs by paying your workers more and abstaining from moving production offshore? Or cut costs and perhaps increase revenues as well, by reducing your dependence on fossil fuels and developing green products?\par \par \uc2 Declarations that companies are going green often involve a lot of grandstanding, self-promotion and exaggeration of small initiatives.\par \par \uc2 Sir Richard managed to make the Virgin Group's investment of Dollars 3bn (Pounds 1.6bn) over 10 years in renewable energy such as biofuels sound as much a virtuous gesture as a smart financial gamble. But so what? Corporate self-interest can be a force for good.\par \par \uc2 The market is voting on whether to do something about global warming and Mr Bush's stance is getting even less endorsement than his party is likely to receive in the November mid-term elections. The president prefers to encourage the voluntary use of alternative fuels while big companies see an opportunity in the legal capping of carbon emissions and trading of emissions allowances.\par \par \uc2 For energy-consuming companies - even for many energy-producing ones - environmental action creates a rare degree of alignment between being socially responsible and increasing shareholder value. At its simplest, they can improve their reputation both for innovation and for environmental awareness by making energy-efficient products such as GE's Evolution-series locomotives.\par \par \uc2 They can also save themselves money by reducing their own use of energy. This plays into the hands of big companies that are used to squeezing costs out of administration and supply chains. DuPont, the chemicals company, estimates that it has saved Dollars 3bn in energy costs since 1990 through measures such as using methane emitted from landfill sites to power its industrial boilers.\par \par \uc2 Wal-Mart's new-found evangelism about the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  strikes some of its critics as an attempt to turn attention away from its employment practices. Perhaps so, but it is also able to save a lot by making small changes. It estimates that it has saved Dollars 25m a year and 100,000 tonnes of carbon dioxide emissions by fitting auxiliary engines to trucks for use when they idle at rest stops.\par \par \uc2 There is another motive for such environmentalism - the belief that Mr Bush's opposition to federal regulation will be unsustainable. US states are passing bills to curb greenhouse gas emissions and80 per cent of companies asked by the Pew Centre on Global Climate Change expected federal regulation by 2015.\par \par \uc2 The most likely form of such regulation is a cap-and-trade initiative similar to the European Union's Emission Trading Scheme. The ETS sets limits on emissions by companies in seven sectors, including power generation and oil refining. They must either keep their emissions within these limits or buy carbon emission allowances from other companies that have surpluses.\par \par \uc2 The scheme offers those who save energy most efficiently a chance to make money. Since permits are free, any company that spends less to save a tonne of carbon emissions than the market rate - currently about Euros 13 (Pounds 8.80) - can make a profit. "If you are a well-run business, cap-and-trade is an opportunity," says Garry Felgate, a director of the Carbon Trust.\par \par \uc2 Nor is the opportunity limited to companies in cap-and-trade schemes. European companies in other sectors, including James Murdoch's BSkyB, are going "carbon neutral" by first cutting emissions as much as possible and then paying others to save energy for them. BSkyB has bought energy "offsets" from a wind power project in New Zealand and a Bulgarian hydro-electric power scheme.\par \par \uc2 Offsets are already being traded on the Chicago Climate Exchange, a voluntary scheme similar to the ETS. That interests big companies such as Wal-Mart, which would like to gain financial credits for initiatives such as devoting extra shelf space to GE's energy-saving fluorescent light bulbs. Andrew Ruben, its vice-president for sustainability, says it would pass the benefits on to customers by cutting the price of the bulbs.\par \par \uc2 The wider the latitude for trading in allowances and offsets, the greater the potential for exploitation. Unless such schemes are well-regulated, companies will be able to gain revenues from energy-saving measures they would have implemented anyway. But it is worth that risk. If the only reason to go green was to look good, the world would be in trouble. Happily, there are profits to be made too.\par \par \uc2 Companies are already gaining by curbing their energy use and devising energy-efficient products. Many of them would benefit further if the US government capped greenhouse gas emissions and allowed them to participate in carbon trading. Mr Bush may not see the appeal of laws to stop global warming but the market is sending a different signal. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 20061002L119.077\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CO\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 wlmrt : \uc2 Wal-Mart Stores, Inc.\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 i64 : \uc2 Retail/Wholesale | i656 : \uc2 Mixed Retailing\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-1