s a benchmark for \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  have been simplified in the hope that more companies will report on their environmental and social impacts. \par \par \uc2 This follows concern that interest in non-financial reporting could otherwise be limited to a handful of multinationals. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Global Reporting Initiative, the Amsterdam-based non-profit agency responsible for drawing up the revised guidelines unveiled yesterday, said the framework included for the first time an "entry-level" option. \par \par \uc2 That meant businesses could choose to report on a limited number of issues, rather than all aspects of sustainable policy. The approach will benefit smaller and medium-sized enterprises that have cited the complexity of existing guidelines as a barrier to non-financial reporting, GRI said. \par \par \uc2 Last month the Financial Times reported a draft United Nations-commissioned study warning that non-financial reporting may play only a limited rolein promoting sustainable development because the practice would be confined largely to transnational corporations in industrialised countries. \par \par \uc2 Achim Steiner, executive director of the UN \b \highlight22\uc2 Environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  Programme that commissioned the report, yesterday said complexity was one factor that gave rise to concern. "We don't want to reach for the stars and find half the people do not even begin the process," he said. \par \par \uc2 Hence, while the "standards of what ultimately would be the highest level of reporting have not been lowered" the process had been "streamlined and made more effective and more accessible". \par \par \uc2 "Over three to five years (a company) can move from the first level to the highest level of reporting," he said. "The excuse that it was too complex is no longer there. The only choice now is to be seen as part of the solution or part of the problem." \par \par \uc2 Referring to the draft report, he said: "It was commissioned to think through various realities. GRI is a remarkable success story but we are on a platform which we must not allow to become a plateau." \par \par \uc2 Ernst Ligteringen, chief executive of GRI, conceded that non-financial reporting was largely confined to leading companies, but pointed out that the number of businesses adopting the guidelines had risen four-fold to more than 2,000 in four years. \par \par \uc2 And there was evidence of increasing interest among suppliers and investors, he said. "For example, Chilean food exporters want to make sure there is confidence in their apples and pears on the shelves in European supermarkets." \par \par \uc2 "It is not whether this kind of information will be needed by markets, it will be needed," Mr Ligteringen said. "It is only a matter of time." \par \par \uc2 The new guidelines were "a major step forward", he said, with a better structure and greater transparency. They were based on 4,000 suggested improvements from trades unions, NGOs and companies. \par \par \uc2 Their presentation was the centrepiece of a conference attended by more than 1,000 businesses and organisations. Keynote speakers included Sir Mark Moody-Stuart, chairman of Anglo American, and Gerard Kleisterlee, chief executive of Philips, the Dutch technology company.  \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt