adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Banking remains a popular career choice for graduates. But there still is a huge difference between working for a traditional high street bank and a City investment bank. In investment banking the lure of multi-million dollar bonuses overshadows the long hours, endless travel and high pressure spent working through the night to negotiate deals. By contrast retail banks are seen as providing a better work-life balance but are also viewed as potentially more staid and less dynamic than investment banking. Investment banks have recognised that potential employees are looking at more than just money. Some new graduates are also interested in corporate and social responsibility programmes and diversity policies. Swiss bank UBS, which selectively hires more than 600 graduates and 550 interns each year from more than 75,000 applications worldwide, is seeking to address feedback from new recruits about the need to work smart - rather than just working long hours. \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Anand David, global head of recruiting at UBS Investment Bank, says: "The feedback we have from first, second and third year analysts in our corporate finance business broadly reflects positive feedback on their training, the breadth of experience they received, and in general they felt UBS was a great firm for which to work. "More concerning is what they are saying about the amount of hours spent in the office. \par \par \uc2 The hours in the office lead to a feeling of a lack of control over their working time and there is a desire to work smarter rather than harder. Given the increasing competition for talent we as an industry cannot afford to ignore this." As a result, he says, the investment banking department has set up two consultative groups, called Work Smart and Lead Smart. Work Smart involves looking at how staff can work harder and share knowledge more effectively. Lead Smart enables management to help mentor and coach the rest of the staff. He says: "UBS is a global financial service firm and cross border billion dollar deals mean long hours advising our clients - and analysts by and large accept this as the operating reality. "However, working smart is as important as working hard and we are exploring how the further leveraging of technology, for instance, can give them control over their time so they do not have to reinvent the wheel - in our case the pitch book." Other investment banks try to entice graduates by bolstering their \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  (CSR) credentials. At Morgan Stanley for example, recruits are given the CSR lowdown on their first day and introduced to the bank's array of community commitments. In the fight for graduate talent, high street banks do stress the attractive worklife balance they can offer. In addition many also stress the breadth of experience and career paths that they can offer to graduates. \par \par \uc2 High street banks like Barclays, HSBC and Royal Bank of Scotland have huge overseas operations so graduates can be posted overseas or work in a variety of areas such as private banking or insurance. Neil Roden, group director of human resources at Royal Bank of Scotland, says that last year RBS, the UK's second largest bank, received 52 applicants per place and had 10,000 applicants for 277 jobs. This year the number of graduate jobs has increased to 515 jobs and it has received 1,100 applications in the first week of recruiting. Around 100 of the posts will be outside the UK. Graduates increasingly have the chance to work outside the UK as RBS is expanding in Europe, US and Asia. Mr Roden says of the differences between retail and investment banks: "We do not have an investment bank culture. We are not in the place where we take the last centimetre out of people. If you are a graduate and work for an investment bank you are the sort of person to deal with high rewards but this means long hours and a fast paced \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 . To a certain degree people self select. "We have 15 different graduate programmes and the perception of being stuck in a bank branch in Leyton has always been a minimal part of what we do."  \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 20061016S419.900\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CO\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 ubs : \uc2 UBS AG\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\c