rleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b SN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Financial Times (FT.Com)\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b SC\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 FTCOM\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LA\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 English\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 (c) 2006 The Financial Times Limited. All rights reserved \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 In last week's column I touched on the question of whether talented managers might be driven from quoted companies into private equity by the burden of corporate governance. This is worth a closer look. For however fast private equity is growing, the proportion of the world's savings tied up in quoted equity remains far greater. It therefore matters a great deal whether good managers are still minding the shop.\par \par \uc2 Begin with an obvious point. Some quoted company CEOs do indeed complain about having greater burdens and lower rewards than their private equity counterparts. But in market language, they are talking their book. Of course they would like less interference and more money. So would we all. What matters is what they actually do about it.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Among interested parties I have spoken to, such as senior directors, investors and headhunters, there is a surprising consensus about that. The top jobs at big public companies are still hotly competed for, and not many of the contenders would see private equity as an alternative.\par \par \uc2 This is because in reality, the two jobs are very different. Private equity gunslingers, to put it bluntly, are motivated primarily by money. They have a low opinion of their public counterparts because they earn less. In the UK, I understand, their collective term for FTSE 100 chief executives is FDH - fat, dumb and happy.\par \par \uc2 But this is to miss the point. Public company CEOs are plainly not indifferent to money, as shown by their rampant wage inflation. But that is chiefly a matter of competition within their peer group. Their main rewards come in the form of status and recognition.\par \par \uc2 As Samuel Johar of the UK headhunters Buchanan Harvey puts it, "FTSE 100 chief executives have the power of patronage. They can write cheques for hundreds of millions and make or break careers. That's why they have the world chasing them".\par \par \uc2 They also have some quite specific skills in handling shareholders and the press. They not only like the limelight, they have to be good at it. In private equity, these talents would be wasted.\par \par \uc2 In addition, as one veteran chairman of large companies put it to me, being CEO of a quoted company actually gives you more freedom. Your shareholders are much more widely distributed than in private equity, and their power is diluted accordingly.\par \par \uc2 So everything is all right, then? Up to a point. For a start, private equity bid targets are getting steadily bigger. KKR recently made an informal $51bn offer for Vivendi, the French media and telecommunications company. Had that gone through, no doubt some heavyweight CEOs would have wanted the job.\par \par \uc2 In addition, the external demands on public company boards are indeed rising. One simple measure is the size of annual reports. The latest from the banking group HSBC is a monstrous 424 pages, and is apparently too heavy to be delivered on regular UK mail runs.\par \par \uc2 That matters, since these are legally binding documents that must be read by directors and discussed at board meetings. Plainly, they should be aware of the facts these reports contain. Whether they should devote so much valuable time to the manner of their publication is another matter.\par \par \uc2 Where is all this stuff coming from? Much of it consists of disclosure requirements laid down by the US regulator. Some of these, such as the risk factors dictated by the SEC's Form 20F, are very useful to investors. Most, though, consist of duplication.\par \par \uc2 In the UK, disclosure is covered by the Combined Code of corporate governance. In the US, where corporate governance and shareholder power are painfully weak by comparison, the gap is filled by regulation. So large UK companies are obliged to comply with two quite different regimes, and forests are levelled in consequence.\par \par \uc2 And then, of course, there are the pressure groups upon \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and so forth. Their demands may be individually slight, but they mount up. BP's annual report proper runs to a mere 177 pages. But its sustainability reports for its countries of operation total almost twice as much again.\par \par \uc2 As for the UK government's recent sudden decision to make companies disclose details of their supply chains, perhaps the less said the better.\par \par \uc2 All in all, then, there is no room for complacency. So far, the CEOs of public companies may be crying wolf. But the point of that fable was one day the wolf turned out to be real.\par \par \uc2 tony.jackson@ft.com \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widct