i0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b SC\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 FTCOM\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LA\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 English\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 (c) 2006 The Financial Times Limited. All rights reserved \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 By Sarah Murray\par \par \uc2 Discussions about environmental stewardship and community development were once heard in the offices of multilateral institutions, development banks and non-profit organisations. Today, as the private sector embraces corporate responsibility, many private sector jobs resemble those once only seen public or voluntary organisations - providing stiff competition for those organisations when it comes to recruitment.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Take Cisco Systems. As vice-president of corporate affairs at the company, Tae Yoo heads a team responsible for creating partnerships with local and global organisations to promote change in such areas as education, basic needs and economic development - a job description that looks very similar to that of someone working in a United Nations agency or a non-governmental organisation (NGO).\par \par \uc2 Much of the activities that go on at Nike, too, are focused on development and sustainability. As a result, the work of its executives ranges from managing labour conditions in clothing and shoe factories to involvement in initiatives such ninemillion.org, a project launched by the UNHCR, the UN's refugee agency, in which Nike, along with companies such as Microsoft, supports efforts to bring education and sports to young people in refugee camps.\par \par \uc2 "You've got greater opportunities than ever before for people who have been in the public sector to move into positions in corporations," says Alan Marks, a senior spokesperson for Nike.\par \par \uc2 Mr Marks cites the work of Sarah Severn, Nike's director of sustainable development, whose job is to examine trends ranging from the depletion of global oil reserves to developments in sustainable design. Ms Severn is also responsible for identifying long-term opportunities and risks in such areas as the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and traditionally excluded populations - issues that were once the concern only of governments and NGOs.\par \par \uc2 "She's trying to look five or even 10 years out at emerging issues in the NGO world and issues that will be of importance to the company," says Mr Marks. "She's been with Nike for a number of years, so she is not someone who came out of the public sector - but the kind of work she's doing is very much in line with public sector work."\par \par \uc2 While executives such as Ms Yoo and Ms Severn come from corporate backgrounds, the drive to embrace corporate responsibility has prompted companies to start persuading public and non-profit sector employees to move across to the for-profit world.\par \par \uc2 At Unilever, for example, Santiago Gowland started two NGOs in Argentina - one focusing on handicapped children, the other on microfinance - before joining the Anglo-Dutch consumer products group as its director of corporate responsibility.\par \par \uc2 Microsoft, too, has recruited staff from the non-profit and public sector, hiring people from development banks, development agencies and large foundations. Pamela Passman, Microsoft's vice-president of global corporate affairs, says these executives bring with them valuable skills as well as insights into the public and voluntary sectors. "We learn a lot from them about the language, how priorities are set and how to make things happen in these organisations," she says.\par \par \uc2 "With the increasing emphasis on the management of corporate responsibility and risks and reporting those areas, there's been a significant increase of recruitment in the private sector of people who have been in the voluntary sector," says Robert Davies, chief executive of the International Business Leaders Forum, which works with corporations to promote responsible business practices.\par \par \uc2 Moreover, he adds, pension fund and institutional investors now require analysts capable of focusing on the social aspects of a business, such as human rights, labour standards and the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 . "And almost none of that existed five years ago," says Mr Davies.\par \par \uc2 As the lines blur between the activities of the public and private sectors, executives who have worked in a variety of organisations- whether governmental, voluntary or multilateral -are becoming highly sought after.\par \par \uc2 "There's a greater premium placed on high level individuals with cross-sectoral experience," says Bennett Freeman, senior vice-president for social research and policy at the Calvert Group, the US family of socially responsible mutual funds. "Ten years ago, there weren't too many people with those kind of credentials and now that is the way of the future."\par \par \uc2 For the global public sector, the trend is clear: stiff competition is emerging when it comes to recruiting top talent to work in areas such as development and sustainability. Moreover, while big institutions such as the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund can offer attractive packages to staff, smaller non-profit groups and non-governmental organisations struggle to compete with private sector salaries.\par \par \uc2 "It's a much more competitive market for the big public institutions and development agencies," says Mr Freeman, who in the late 1990s worked in government as US deputy assistant secretary of state for democracy, human rights and labour.\par \par \uc2 "These organisations no longer have a corner on the market for the best jobs and the greatest responsibilities." \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 52735146\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 ccsr : \uc2 Corporate Social Responsibility | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | ncat : \uc2 Content Types | nfact : \uc2 Factiva Filters | nfcpex : \uc2 FC&E Executive News Filter\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RE\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 uk : \uc2 United Kingdom | eecz : \uc2 European Union Countries | eurz : \uc2 Europe | weurz : \uc2 Western Europe\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trow