sh\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 (Copyright (c) 2006, Dow Jones & Company, Inc.) \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 WHEN L. FRANK BROWN, a 26-year veteran of PriceWaterhouseCoopers, took over as dean of Insead in July, it marked a major departure for the 45-year-old international business school. He is a business executive from outside the school who doesn't hold a master's degree in business administration, at a school that has traditionally filled the post from within its own faculty.\par \par \uc2 An accounting buff with a bachelor's degree from Bucknell University, the New Jersey native is also only the second American in Insead's history to serve as dean.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 In a telephone interview from his office in Fontainebleau, France, site of one of Insead's two campuses -- the other is in Singapore -- Mr. Brown spoke with The Wall Street Journal about what's on the agenda at Insead, including raising the school's profile and promoting programs in transcultural leadership and \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 The Wall Street Journal: Since your appointment was announced late last year, there's been a lot of talk about you in management-education circles. The most-asked question seems to be, "Why did Insead decide to hire a business professional without an M.B.A. academic background to run the school?"\par \par \uc2 Mr. Brown: Both the faculty and the board were looking for a businessperson with more real business experience and a business perspective. . . . I think there was generally a feeling that such a person could help us get to our next stage of growth.\par \par \uc2 I have a different eye, a different view, and so I come in and look at things in a lot of different ways and bring a new perspective.\par \par \uc2 WSJ: You have said that you'd like to increase emphasis on ethics and \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 . What, concretely, can be done?\par \par \uc2 Mr. Brown: Actually, the students themselves are more focused on it. Certainly in terms of ethics, a component is included in every discussion. I've encouraged students to have healthy debates about how to conduct yourself in various business scenarios. . . . The ethical component is here and it's going to continue to be a focus.\par \par \uc2 The bigger issue is the CSR component. Here again, developments on campus have been student-led. We have a student club here focused on CSR and it's one of the most popular. Students do programs in the community, and many of them are interested in going into the NGO [nongovernmental organization] field. We've brought someone into our career-services network to help in that respect.\par \par \uc2 On the institutional side, we've got studies under way on both campuses to see how to use less energy and less water. It is becoming much more of a focus here. A lot of good things are happening on our campuses but they are not as well coordinated as I'd like to see them. I don't want to overstructure the place, but I do want to create an \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  where people can see what their colleagues are doing.\par \par \uc2 WSJ: What has been your biggest challenge so far?\par \par \uc2 Mr. Brown: The biggest challenge that we have is communicating the Insead brand. . . . I'm amazed how many people know the name Insead but how few people know what Insead really is. Most people, for instance, don't know that we have two campuses. A lot of people don't know that ours is a one-year program, or that we have a significant commitment to a Ph.D. program, or that we are a research-based institution.\par \par \uc2 WSJ: When you were appointed you said that you hope to increase awareness of Insead in the U.S. What have you done so far to make Insead a more recognized brand in your native country?\par \par \uc2 Mr. Brown: I am using my network and going to people in the business world whom I already know. I'm also leveraging our alumni in the U.S. We have about 4,000 alumni in the U.S., and we have to build more of a relationship with them so that they're more vocal about their relations with us.\par \par \uc2 I also firmly believe that Insead needs an official office in the U.S. I'm not talking about a campus, but there needs to be a place in the U.S. for us to be able to connect to our alumni, as well as perhaps to do some executive education. That should be part of our plan.\par \par \uc2 With an official office, I'm not talking about replacing the Wharton alliance [an exchange program with the University of Pennsylvania's Wharton School], which has been very beneficial for both of us and will continue to be so. But I do think that Insead needs its own presence in the U.S., from both a branding and an alumni-connection standpoint.\par \par \uc2 WSJ: What else is on your wish list?\par \par \uc2 Mr. Brown: No. 1 is to really build the brand, as I've mentioned. But I think that the Insead brand should become more synonymous with the word "leadership," and specifically "transcultural leadership." We really do generate people at Insead with a unique perspective on the world. Our participants have an ability to navigate across geography and across cultures and really have a significant impact on organizations.\par \par \uc2 I would like that to become part of the DNA of our brand; I would like us to do more research into transcultural leadership, and also to develop a leadership center. We have lots of research and lots of people doing work on the subject of leadership, but it's not as well-organized or as well-funded as I would like it to be.\par \par \uc2 No. 2 on my wish list is further increasing diversity. . . . I'd like us to offer more scholarships to increase diversity. And I'd like to focus on women, on people from Africa, South America and other places underrepresented in our student body. . . . I've been talking with alumni about the need to improve that. I hope our $100 million [endowment] will increase dramatically and help us to do so.\par \par \uc2 WSJ: Insead has announced some new ventures, including a new executive-education center in Abu Dhabi and a regional research center in Israel. Are these announcements part of a wider development strategy in the Middle East?\par \par \uc2 Mr. Brown: Absolutely. One of my views is that education is the key to the future success of the region. There are large amounts of unemployment, which has probably been fostered by huge amounts of oil wealth. And the government of Abu Dhabi, for instance, is now looking for education to help in that respect. We want to partner with the government in the area of higher education.I've been really impressed with the government there and the efforts that they are making in this respect.\par \par \uc2 Some Insead faculty members also are developing executive-education or other academic programs for companies in the region and also using it as a way to attract talented students from the region to do their M.B.A. degrees in Fontainebleau or in Singapore.\par \par \uc2 WSJ: Are there any specific plans for further development in Asia?\par \par \uc2 Mr. Brown: We have lots of programs. Last April we ran a program in India where we lined up a dozen CEOs from Indian companies to meet with our M.B.A. students, and each CEO spent half a day with 30 students, over six days, and talked about their businesses.\par \par \uc2 We also will launch our dual-degree executive M.B.A. with Tsinghua University's School of Economics and Management in June. The target is to have about 45 people [at first], roughly half in Singapore and half in Beijing. \par \par {\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw119\pich200\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal1785\pichgoal3000
