t-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LA\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 English\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 (Copyright (c) 2007, Dow Jones & Company, Inc.) \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 FOUNDATIONS ARE JOINING the corporate-responsibility movement, pressing companies to conform with the foundations' philanthropic goals.\par \par \uc2 For much of its history, the Nathan Cummings Foundation managed its endowment for maximum returns. Then five years ago, it embarked on a new course for the philanthropy world: using its stock portfolio to urge public companies to change practices that go against the foundation's mission, which in Cummings's case involves health, the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the arts.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Last year, the $522 million foundation, whose founder created the company that became Sara Lee, participated in 13 shareholder resolutions, up from two in 2003. Key actions included attempts to get Bed, Bath &Beyond, Home Depot and Simon Property Group to improve the energy efficiency of their stores, and to demand greater disclosure of greenhouse emissions by Ultra Petroleum and Valero Energy. Whether these proxies garner many votes or not, the idea is to get the foundation's ideas on the company's agenda, and jump-start conversations with company management.\par \par \uc2 A small number of nonprofits -- including the Needmor Fund, the Jessie Smith Noyes Foundation and the Boston Foundation -- have embraced proxy activism in recent years. But most foundation boards have been reluctant to do so. One issue is the cultural divide between the financial managers who oversee foundation endowments and the executives who give away the money. Generally speaking, finance officials are judged on the returns on their investments, while grant-makers aren't well-versed in the financial world. "They don't speak the same language so they don't trust each other's information," says Michael Passoff, an associate director at As You Sow, a San Francisco nonprofit that promotes \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Now, though, more foundations are voting their proxies according to their philanthropic missions. Among new converts: the Rockefeller Brothers Fund and the Rhode Island Foundation. In November, the $640 million Skoll Foundation convened about a dozen Northern California foundations to discuss the concept. That same month, Skoll's own board approved voting its proxies to back its priorities, which include the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and health care.\par \par \uc2 The biggest private foundation of all, the almost $32 billion Bill &Melinda Gates Foundation, takes a more passive role toward its investments "because we want to stay focused on our core issues," said the foundation's chief operating officer, Cheryl Scott, in a statement released last week. She was responding to articles in the Los Angeles Times that said the practices of some of the companies in which Gates invests run counter to the foundation's goals, which include boosting health care and easing poverty.\par \par \uc2 Some activists say a foundation should simply sell its stock in companies whose practices are at odds with the foundation's philosophy. But that amounts to criticizing companies from afar rather than encouraging them to change from within, say proxy-voting supporters. By taking part in shareholder resolutions, "we have a voice," says Lance Lindblom, Cummings's chief executive.\par \par \uc2 ---\par \par \uc2 Contact us at givingback@wsj.com\par \par \uc2 ---\par \par \uc2 GIFT OF THE WEEK\par \par \uc2 Help From MBA No. 1\par \par \uc2 WHO GAVE IT: William Hough, founder of an investment-banking firm in St. Petersburg, Fla.\par \par \uc2 HOW MUCH: $30 million\par \par \uc2 WHO GOT IT: The University of Florida's Warrington College of Business\par \par \uc2 YOUR NAME HERE: The Hough Graduate School of Business and William R. Hough Hall\par \par \uc2 BY REQUEST: $25 million will increase the graduate school's endowment, and $5 million will help construct its new building\par \par \uc2 HOW IT HAPPENED: The Navy sent Mr. Hough to college in Ohio as part of his officer training. But once World War II was over, he headed to his hometown of St. Petersburg, Fla., and then to a school he'd always dreamed of attending, the University of Florida in Gainesville. He bunked at the Kappa Sigma fraternity and cheered on the Gator athletic teams. In 1948, he became the university's first M.B.A. graduate.\par \par \uc2 Now 80, he's able to once again spend considerable time on campus, after selling his financial firm, William R. Hough &Co., in 2004. (It had 250 employees and $50 million in capital at the time.) This year he didn't come out solely to watch the champion football team, though; he also guest-lectured to the school's 700 M.B.A. students. His gift is the largest received by the university, but it follows 20 years of donations by Mr. Hough, ranging up to $200,000, to aid the business program. "We're trying to make the business school a place our athletes can be proud of," he jokes.\par \par \uc2 -- Kelly Crow\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.djreprints.com/link/DJRFactiva.html?FACTIVA=wjco20070119000060"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 License this article from Dow Jones Reprint Service}}}\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 ccsr : \uc2 Corporate Social Responsibility | gedu : \uc2 Education | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | gcat : \uc2 Political/General News | ncat : \uc2 Content Types | nfact : \uc2 Factiva Filters | nfcpex : \uc2 FC&E Executive News Filter\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\c